{"title_page": "Salman of Saudi Arabia", "text_new": "{{redirect-distinguish|King Salman|King Solomon|King Salmon (disambiguation){{!}}King Salmon}}\n{{short description|King of Saudi Arabia}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2017}}\n{{POV|date=August 2019}}\n{{Infobox royalty\n|name        = Salman bin Abdulaziz Al Saud\n|image       = Salman of Saudi Arabia - 2020 (49563590728) (cropped).jpg\n|caption     = Salman bin Abdulaziz Al Saud in February 2020\n|succession  = {{plainlist|\n*[[King of Saudi Arabia]]\n*[[Prime Minister of Saudi Arabia]]\n*[[Custodian of the Two Holy Mosques]]}}\n|reign       = 23 January 2015 \u2013 present\n|coronation  = 23 January 2015 \n|cor-type    = [[Bay'ah]]\n|predecessor = [[Abdullah of Saudi Arabia|Abdullah]]\n|successor   = {{plainlist|\n*[[Muqrin bin Abdulaziz]] (2015)\n*[[Muhammad bin Nayef]] (2015&ndash;17)\n*[[Mohammad bin Salman]] (2017&ndash;present)}}\n|suc-type    = {{nowrap|Heir apparent}}\n|birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1935|12|31|df=y}}\n|birth_place = [[Riyadh]], [[Saudi Arabia]]\n|issue       ={{Collapsible list|[[Fahd bin Salman bin Abdulaziz Al Saud|Fahd]]|\n[[Sultan bin Salman Al Saud|Sultan]]|\n[[Ahmed bin Salman bin Abdulaziz Al Saud|Ahmed]]|\n[[Abdulaziz bin Salman Al Saud|Abdulaziz]]|\n[[Faisal bin Salman bin Abdulaziz Al Saud|Faisal]]|\n[[Hassa bint Salman Al Saud|Hassa]]|\n[[Saud Bin Salman bin Abdulaziz al Saud|Saud]]|\n[[Mohammad bin Salman|Mohammad]]|\n[[Turki bin Salman Al Saud|Turki]]|\n[[Khalid bin Salman bin Abdulaziz Al Saud|Khalid]]|\nNayif|\nBandar|\nRakan}}\n|issue-link  = #Personal life\n|full name   = Salman bin Abdulaziz bin Abdul Rahman bin Faisal bin Turki bin Abdullah bin Mohammed bin Saud\n|house       = [[House of Saud]]\n|father      = [[Ibn Saud]]\n|mother      = [[Hassa bint Ahmed Al Sudairi|Hassa bint Ahmad Al Sudairi]]\n|signature   =\n|spouse = {{plainlist|\n*Sultana bint Turki Al Sudairi (deceased in 2011)\n*Sarah bint Faisal Al Subai'ai (divorced)\n*Fahda bint Falah Al Sultan}}\n}}\n\n'''Salman bin Abdulaziz Al Saud''' ({{lang-ar|\u0633\u0644\u0645\u0627\u0646 \u0628\u0646 \u0639\u0628\u062f \u0627\u0644\u0639\u0632\u06cc\u0632 \u0622\u0644 \u0633\u0639\u0648\u062f}} ''{{transl|ar|ALA|Salm\u0101n ibn \u2018Abd al-\u2018Az\u012bz \u0100l Su\u2018\u016bd}}'', <small>[[Najdi Arabic]] pronunciation:</small> {{IPA-ar|s\u00e6l\u02c8m\u00e6\u02d0n ben \u02c8\u02a2\u00e6bd \u00e6l\u02a2\u00e6\u02c8zi\u02d0z \u0294\u00e6\u02d0l s\u00e6\u02c8\u02a2u\u02d0d|}}; born 31 December 1935) has been the [[King of Saudi Arabia|king]] and [[Prime Minister of Saudi Arabia|prime minister]] of [[Saudi Arabia]] and [[custodian of the Two Holy Mosques]] since 23 January 2015.\n\nHe was the deputy governor of [[Riyadh Province|Riyadh]] and later the governor of Riyadh for 48 years from 1963 to 2011. He was then appointed minister of Defense. He was also named the [[Crown Prince of Saudi Arabia|crown prince]] in 2012 following the death of his brother [[Nayef bin Abdulaziz]]. Salman became the new king of Saudi Arabia on 23 January 2015 following the death of his half-brother, [[Abdullah of Saudi Arabia|King Abdullah]]. Since 2019 he is also the oldest surviving son of [[Ibn Saud]].\n\nHis major initiatives as king include the [[Operation Decisive Storm|Saudi intervention]] in the [[Yemeni Civil War (2015\u2013present)|Yemeni Civil War]], [[Saudi Vision 2030]], and a 2017 decree allowing Saudi women to drive. His son, Crown Prince [[Mohammad bin Salman]], is considered the ''de facto'' ruler of Saudi Arabia and has led many reforms within the country, as well as engendering a number of controversies, including the [[2017\u201319 Saudi Arabian purge|2017 arrest of members of the Saudi royal family]] and the [[killing of Jamal Khashoggi]].\u0648\u0627\u0644\u0641\u0627\u062c\u0631 \u064a\u062e\u0644\u064a \u0627\u0644\u0631\u0648\u0645 \u0648 \u0627\u0644\u0646\u0635\u0627\u0631\u064a \u064a\u062d\u062c\u0648 \u0648 \u064a\u062f\u062e\u0644 \u062f\u064a\u0646 \u0627\u0647\u0644 \u0627\u0639\u062f\u0627\u0621 \u0627\u0644\u0644\u0647 \u0627\u0644\u0643\u0639\u0628\u0629 \u0648\u0627\u0646\u0627 \u0645\u0634 \u0639\u0627\u0631\u0641 \u0627\u0631\u0648\u062d \u0627\u0628\u0646 \u062f\u064a\u0646 \u0627\u0644\u0643\u0644\u0628 \u0627\u0644\u0641\u0627\u062c\u0631 \n\u0627\u0632\u0627\u064a \u0642\u0648\u0645 \u0641\u0631\u0639\u0648\u0646 \u0627\u0644\u064a \u0647\u0648\u0627 \u0627\u0646\u062a\u0648 \n\u0643\u062f\u0627 \u061f\u061f\n\u0627\u0641\u0644\u0627 \u062a\u0639\u0642\u0644\u0648\u0646 \n\u0648\u0628\u0639\u062f\u064a\u0646 \u064a\u062d\u0643\u0645 \u0639\u0644\u064a\u0627 \u0632\u064a \u0627\u0644\u0645\u0644\u0643 \u0648 \u064a\u0642\u0648\u0644 \u0627\u0639\u0645\u0644\u0648 \u0645\u0639\u0627\u0647 \n\u0627\u0644\u064a \u0627\u062e\u062a\u0634\u0648 \u0645\u0627\u062a\u0648 \u0648\u0627\u0644\u0644\u0647\n\n==Early life==\nSalman was born on 31 December 1935, and is reported to be the 25th son of [[Ibn Saud]], the first monarch and founder of Saudi Arabia.<ref name=\"Aawsat\"/> Salman and his six full brothers make up the [[Sudairi Seven]].<ref name=thedip12>{{cite journal|title=An Heir to the Kingdom: New Crown Prince Salman|journal=The Diplomat|date=July\u2013August 2012|volume=35|pages=8\u201311|url=http://www.ids.gov.sa/sites/ar/Diplomat/Book%20Diplomat%2035.pdf|accessdate=9 February 2013}}</ref><ref>Alexander Bligh. From Prince to King; Succession to the throne in Saudi Arabia. New York, New York University Press (1984). Arabic edition: Alexander Bligh. Min amir ila malik. London, D.A. Publications (1989).</ref> He was raised in the [[Murabba Palace]].<ref name=nbhf/>\n\nSalman received his early education at the [[Princes' School]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Arab Rulers' Academic Degrees, Majors at a Glance|url=https://ifpnews.com/exclusive/arab-rulers-academic-degrees/|accessdate=20 January 2019}}</ref> in the capital city of [[Riyadh]], a school established by Ibn Saud specifically to provide education for his children.<ref name=moi>{{cite web|title=His royal highness Prince Salman bin Abdulaziz|url=http://www.riyadh.gov.sa/en/Pages/Princes/Princes.aspx?ItemId=5|work=Ministry of Interior|accessdate=12 May 2012|url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130930121212/http://www.riyadh.gov.sa/en/Pages/Princes/Princes.aspx?ItemId=5 |archivedate=30 September 2013}}</ref> He studied religion and modern science.<ref name=sew1>{{cite web|title=Ministers with portfolio|url=http://www.saudiembassy.net/print/about/Biographies-of-Ministers.aspx|work=Saudi Embassy, Washington DC|accessdate=19 June 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120607004102/http://www.saudiembassy.net/print/about/Biographies-of-Ministers.aspx|archivedate=7 June 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Governor of Riyadh==\n[[File:Vladimir Putin in Saudi Arabia 11-12 February 2007-14.jpg|thumb|Governor Salman bin Abdulaziz with [[Vladimir Putin]] in 2007]] Salman was appointed deputy governor of [[Riyadh Province]] in 17 March 1954, aged 19, and held the post until 19 April 1955.<ref name=\"Aawsat\">{{cite web|title=Profile: New Saudi Defense Minister Prince Salman bin Abdulaziz |url=http://www.aawsat.net/2011/11/article55244468 |work=Asharq Al-Awsat |accessdate=14 February 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150214200738/http://www.aawsat.net/2011/11/article55244468 |archivedate=14 February 2015 |df= }}</ref> He was appointed the provincial governor in 5 February 1963,<ref name=moi/> and remained in that office until 5 November 2011.<ref name=sew1/>\n\nAs governor, he contributed to the development of [[Riyadh]] from a mid-sized town into a major urban metropolis. He served as an important liaison to attract tourism, capital projects and foreign investment to his country. He favored political and economic relationships with the West.<ref name=pbs/> During his governorship, Salman recruited advisors from [[King Saud University]].<ref>Joseph A. Kechichian. Succession in Saudi Arabia. New York: Palgrave, 2001. Print.</ref>\n\nDuring Salman's five decades as Riyadh governor, he became adept at managing the delicate balance of clerical, tribal, and princely interests that determine Saudi policy.<ref>[http://uk.businessinsider.com/heres-everything-we-know-about-the-new-saudi-king-2015-1?r=US Here's Everything We Know About The New Saudi King] Business Insider. 23 January 2015. Retrieved 27 January 2015.</ref> He was also the chairman of the King Abdulaziz Foundation for Research and Archives (KAFRA),<ref>{{cite news|last=M. Taha|first=Sharif|title=Sharjah ruler among 18 to be honored by Prince Salyman|url=http://arabnews.com/saudiarabia/article626065.ece|accessdate=12 May 2012|newspaper=Arab News|date=5 May 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120509193610/http://arabnews.com/saudiarabia/article626065.ece|archivedate=9 May 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> King Abdulaziz Museum,<ref name=anews08>{{cite news|title=In-Depth Study of King Faisal's Life Urged |url=http://archive.arabnews.com/?page=1&section=0&article=109790&d=11&m=5&y=2008 |accessdate=8 June 2012 |newspaper=Arab News |date=11 May 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120616061137/http://archive.arabnews.com/?page=1 |archivedate=16 June 2012 |df= }}</ref> the [[Prince Salman Center for Disability Research]] and the Prince Fahd bin Salman Charitable Society for the Care of Kidney Patients.<ref name=\"Aawsat\"/>\n\nKing Salman also undertook several foreign tours while he was governor. In 1974, he visited [[Kuwait]], [[Bahrain]] and [[Qatar]] to strengthen Saudi Arabia's relationship with those nations. During his visit to [[Montreal]], Canada in 1991, he inaugurated a gallery. In 1996, he was received in the [[\u00c9lys\u00e9e Palace]] in [[Paris]] by the then-French president [[Jacques Chirac]]. The same year he toured [[Bosnia and Herzegovina]] to give donations to the Muslim citizens of the country. Being a part of an Asian tour in 1998, Salman visited [[Pakistan]], [[Japan]], [[Brunei]]<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Cafiero|first=Giorgio|last2=Karasik|first2=Theodore|year=2017|title=King Salman's Return to Brunei Two Decades Later|url=http://nbn-resolving.de/urn:nbn:de:0168-ssoar-50995-9|journal=IndraStra Global|issue=3|page=5}}</ref> and [[China]].<ref>{{cite web|title=\u0627\u0644\u062c\u0648\u0644\u0627\u062a \u0627\u0644\u062e\u0627\u0631\u062c\u064a\u0629 \u0644\u0633\u0644\u0645\u0627\u0646.. \u062f\u0639\u0645 \u0644\u0644\u0639\u0644\u0627\u0642\u0627\u062a \u0648\u062a\u0639\u0632\u064a\u0632 \u0644\u0644\u0631\u0624\u064a\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0633\u0639\u0648\u062f\u064a\u0629|url=http://www.al-madina.com/node/386509|work=Al Madina|accessdate=14 February 2015}}</ref>\n\nAccording to the ''Washington Post'', Saudi journalist the late [[Jamal Khashoggi]] \"criticized Prince Salman, then governor of Riyadh and head of the Saudi committee for support to the [[mujahideen|Afghan mujahideen]], for unwisely funding [[Salafism|Salafist]] extremist groups that were undermining the war [in Afghanistan against the Soviets].\"<ref name=\"ignatius\">{{cite news |title=Jamal Khashoggi's long road to the doors of the Saudi Consulate |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/global-opinions/jamal-khashoggis-long-road-to-the-doors-of-the-saudi-consulate/2018/10/12/b461d6f4-ce1a-11e8-920f-dd52e1ae4570_story.html?noredirect=on |work=The Washington Post |date=12 October 2018}}</ref>\n\nUnder Salman, Riyadh became one of the richest cities in the Middle East and an important place for trade and commerce. There were also infrastructural advances including schools, universities and sports stadiums.<ref name=\"Aawsat\"/> About the province, he said:\n\n<blockquote>Every village or town in the Riyadh Region is dear to me, and holds a special place in my heart&nbsp;... I witnessed every step taken by the city of Riyadh, and for this reason it is difficult for me to think about being far away from Riyadh.<ref name=\"Aawsat\"/> </blockquote>\n\n==Second in line==\n[[File:Leon Panetta with Prince Salman bin Abd al-Aziz Al Saud at the Pentagon April 2012.jpg|thumb|US Secretary of Defense [[Leon Panetta]] with Salman at the [[The Pentagon|Pentagon]] in April 2012]]\nOn 5 November 2011, Salman was appointed Second Deputy Prime Minister and [[Armed Forces of Saudi Arabia|Minister of Defense]], replacing his full brother, the late [[Sultan bin Abdulaziz|Crown Prince Sultan]] (at Defense).<ref name=\"bbcn2011\">{{cite news|title=Saudi Arabia names Prince Salman as new defence minister|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-middle-east-15607814|accessdate=26 May 2012|publisher=BBC News|date=5 November 2011}}</ref> [[Sattam bin Abdul Aziz|Prince Sattam bin Abdulaziz]] was named governor of Riyadh Province. Prince Salman was also named a member of the [[National Security Council (Saudi Arabia)|National Security Council (NSC)]] on the same day.<ref name=\"aps27oct\">{{cite news|title=The Allegiance Council|url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/The+Allegiance+Council.-a0272373988|accessdate=16 March 2013|work=APS Diplomat News Service|date=27 October 2011}}</ref>\n\nIt is speculated that he was placed in the immediate line of succession due to his personal qualities. First, he has a conciliatory and diplomatic nature. He headed the family council, called The Descendants' Council (''Majlis al Uthra'' in Arabic), that was established by King Fahd in 2000 to solve family matters, reach consensus and try to avoid any publicly embarrassing behaviour by some family members.<ref name=tk2712>{{cite web|last=Kapoor|first=Talal|title=Nayif's Passing \u2013 The Family Regroups|url=http://www.datarabia.com/royals/viewCommentary.do?id=88025|work=Datarabia|accessdate=7 July 2012|date=2 July 2012}}</ref><ref name=ata>{{cite journal|author=Amir Taheri|title=Saudi Arabia: Change Begins within the Family|journal=The Journal of the National Committee on American Foreign Policy|year=2012|volume=34|issue=3|pages=138\u2013143|doi=10.1080/10803920.2012.686725}}</ref> Second, Salman belongs to the \"middle generation\" in the royal family; therefore, he could develop close ties with both generations socially and culturally. Last, as a result of his long-term governorship, he had developed a network of relationships within Arab and international circles.<ref name=\"alakhbar\" />\n\nSalman continued the policy of [[Saudi-led intervention in Bahrain|military intervention in Bahrain]], to try to crush the [[Bahrain uprising]]. In April 2012, Salman visited both the United States and the United Kingdom where he met with US President [[Barack Obama]] and British Prime Minister [[David Cameron]].<ref name=tarabia12>{{cite news|title=Saudi Prince dead, Salman likely successor|url=http://www.tradearabia.com/news/LAW_219067.html|accessdate=17 June 2012|work=Trade Arabia|date=16 June 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"gsn21jun12\">{{cite journal|title=Al Saud move with speed to reconfigure top team after Nayef's death|journal=Gulf States Newsletter|date=21 June 2012|volume=36|issue=926|url=http://www.gsn-online.com/sites/default/files/GSN%20926.pdf|accessdate=23 February 2013}}</ref> 2013 saw Saudi military spending climb to $67bn, overtaking that of the UK, France and Japan to place fourth globally.<ref>\"Saudis lead Middle East military spending\". 14 April 2014. Al Jazeera. Retrieved 14 April 2014.</ref> As defense minister, Salman was head of the military as Saudi Arabia joined the United States and other Arab countries in carrying out airstrikes against the Islamic State in Iraq and Syria in 2014.\n\n==Crown Prince==\n[[File:Secretary of Defense Chuck Hagel meets with Crown Prince and Minister of Defense Salman bin Abdulaziz al Saud in Riyadh, Saudi Arabia, April 23, 2013 (Pic 2).jpg|thumb|Crown Prince Salman meeting US Secretary of Defense [[Chuck Hagel]], 23 April 2013]]\nOn 18 June 2012, Salman was appointed as [[Crown Prince of Saudi Arabia]] shortly after the death of his brother, Crown Prince [[Nayef bin Abdul-Aziz Al Saud]].<ref name=bbcnom>{{cite news|last=Patrick|first=Neil|title=Saudi Arabia: Crown Prince's death raises succession questions|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-middle-east-18494785|accessdate=17 June 2012|publisher=BBC|date=17 June 2012}}</ref><ref name=dav19june>{{cite journal|last=Roberts|first=David|title=Saudi Succession after the Death of Crown Prince Nayef|journal=RUSI Analysis|date=19 June 2012|url=http://www.rusi.org/go.php?structureID=commentary&ref=C4FE08BAF7F8BE|accessdate=12 April 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130605181424/http://www.rusi.org/go.php?structureID=commentary&ref=C4FE08BAF7F8BE|archivedate=5 June 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Prince Salman was also made First Deputy Prime minister.<ref name=reu1812/> His nomination as crown prince and deputy prime minister was seen by some as a signal that [[Abdullah of Saudi Arabia|King Abdullah]]'s cautious reforms were likely to continue.<ref name=reu1812>{{cite news|author-link=Angus McDowall|last=McDowall|first=Angus|title=Saudi appoints Prince Salman as crown prince|url=http://uk.reuters.com/article/2012/06/18/uk-saudi-crownprince-appointment-idUKBRE85H15K20120618|accessdate=18 June 2012|agency=Reuters|date=18 June 2012}}</ref> On the other hand, Saudi reformists stated that while Prince Salman, in contrast to other Saudi royals, took a more diplomatic approach towards them, he could not be considered a political reformer.<ref name=ft1226>{{cite news|last=Allam|first=Abeer|title=Saudi Arabia: In a restless realm|url=http://www.ft.com/intl/cms/s/0/59c7492e-e07b-11e1-9335-00144feab49a.html|accessdate=26 August 2012|newspaper=Financial Times|date=26 August 2012}}</ref> They also argued that, like King Abdullah, Salman focused mainly on economic improvement rather than political change.<ref name=ft1226/>\n\nOn 27 August 2012, the Royal Court announced that Salman was in charge of state affairs whilst King Abdullah was out of the country.<ref name=reuriaydh>{{cite news|title=Crown prince in charge as Saudi king leaves on holiday|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2012/08/27/us-saudi-king-travel-idUSBRE87Q0H120120827|accessdate=27 August 2012|agency=Reuters|date=27 August 2012|location=Riyadh}}</ref> Prince Salman launched a [[Twitter]] account on 23 February 2013.<ref name=aa26feb>{{cite news|title=Saudi Crown Prince Salman launches Twitter account|url=http://english.alarabiya.net/articles/2013/02/26/268493.html|accessdate=3 March 2013|publisher=Al Arabiya|date=26 February 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130226205133/http://english.alarabiya.net/articles/2013/02/26/268493.html|archive-date=26 February 2013|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>  In September 2012, Salman was named as the deputy chairman of the military service council.<ref>{{cite news|title=Saudi- Authority to monitor audiovisual media |url=http://www.menafn.com/menafn/1093553820/Saudi-Authority-to-monitor-audiovisual-media |accessdate=4 September 2012 |work=MEFAFN |date=4 September 2012 |agency=Arab News |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140814005012/http://www.menafn.com/menafn/1093553820/Saudi-Authority-to-monitor-audiovisual-media |archivedate=14 August 2014 |df= }}</ref> He is a strong advocate for [[philanthropy]] in poor Muslim nations such as [[Somalia]], [[Sudan]], [[Bangladesh]] and [[Afghanistan]].<ref name=pbs/>\n\n==King of Saudi Arabia==\n[[File:King Salman bin Abdulaziz of Saudi Arabia bids farewell to President Barack Obama at Erga Palace in Riyadh, Saudi Arabia.jpg|thumb|left|US President [[Barack Obama]] shakes hands with King Salman, Riyadh, 27 January 2015]]\n\nOn 23 January 2015, Salman, aged 79, inherited the throne after his half-brother Abdullah died of [[pneumonia]] at the age of 90. The new king issued a statement which read \"His Highness Salman bin Abdulaziz Al Saud and all members of the family and the nation mourn [[Custodian of the Two Holy Mosques]] King Abdullah bin Abdulaziz, who passed away at exactly 1 am this morning.\" He appointed his younger half-brother [[Muqrin of Saudi Arabia|Prince Muqrin]] as the [[Crown Prince of Saudi Arabia|Crown Prince]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Saudi Arabia buries its king: Thousands gather in Mecca as King Abdullah is laid to rest in Riyadh after losing battle with pneumonia|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-2922592/Has-Saudi-Arabia-s-King-Abdullah-died-battle-pneumonia.html#v-4006896776001|work=Daily Mail|accessdate=17 February 2015}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Secretary Kerry Walks With Saudi King Salman After He Arrived At Andrews Air Force Base Before Meeting With President Obama (21098397176).jpg|thumb|US Secretary of State [[John Kerry]] with Salman at [[Andrews Field|Andrews Air Force Base]] in Camp Springs, Maryland, 3 September 2015]]\n[[File:Jokowi Salman 2017 crop.jpg|thumb|King Salman and Indonesian President [[Joko Widodo]] in [[Jakarta]], 1 March 2017]]\nAfter coming to power, Salman reshuffled the cabinet on 30 January 2015. Khalid bin Ali bin Abdullah al-Humaidan was made the [[Al Mukhabarat Al A'amah|intelligence chief]]. [[Prince Bandar bin Sultan]] was removed from his post in the [[Saudi National Security Council|security council]] and the adviser to the monarch was also removed as were the former monarch's sons [[Turki bin Abdullah Al Saud|Turki]] as governor of [[Riyadh]] and [[Mishaal bin Abdullah Al Saud|Mishaal]] as governor of [[Mecca]]. [[Ali al-Naimi]] remained the minister of [[Ministry of Petroleum and Mineral Resources of Saudi Arabia|petroleum and mineral resources]], as did [[Saud al-Faisal]] of the [[Ministry of Foreign Affairs]] and [[Ibrahim Abdulaziz Al-Assaf|Ibrahim Al-Assaf]] as [[Ministry of Finance (Saudi Arabia)|finance minister]]. Salman also \"gave a bonus of two months' salary to all Saudi state employees and military personnel\", including pensioners and students, while also asking citizens to \"not forget me in your prayers\".<ref>{{cite web|title=Saudi Arabia's King Salman unveils cabinet reshuffle|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-31052071|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=3 February 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2015, he received [[Prince Charles]] during his six-day tour in the Middle East. They \"exchanged cordial talks and reviewed bilateral relations\" between the countries.<ref>{{cite web|title=King Salman receives Prince Charles in Riyadh|url=http://english.alarabiya.net/en/News/middle-east/2015/02/10/Saudi-King-Salman-receives-Prince-Charles-in-Riyadh-.html|publisher=Al Arabiya|accessdate=14 February 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Early reforms===\nOne of the first things the King and his son, [[Mohammad bin Salman]], did was to streamline the government bureaucracy. On the death of King Abdullah, there were as many as eleven government secretariats, and all of these were abolished and reconstituted as only two, the [[Council of Political and Security Affairs (Saudi Arabia)|Council of Political and Security Affairs]] (CPSA), headed by Deputy Crown prince [[Mohammed bin Nayef]], and the [[Council of Economic and Development Affairs (Saudi Arabia)|Council for Economic and Development Affairs]] (CEDA), headed by the Secretary-General of the Royal Court, Prince Mohammad bin Salman, who were given free rein to completely reorganize the government<ref>[http://gulfnews.com/news/gulf/saudi-arabia/mohammad-bin-nayef-takes-leading-role-in-saudi-arabia-1.1458374 Mohammad bin Nayef takes leading role in Saudi Arabia] ''Gulf News''. 17 February 2015. Retrieved 13 March 2015.</ref> and cementing the power of the Sudairi faction, to which both princes belong.\n\n===Yemen military intervention===\n{{main|Saudi Arabian-led intervention in Yemen}}\nIn March 2015, the king ordered the bombing of Yemen and [[Saudi Arabian-led intervention in Yemen|military intervention]] against the [[Shia Islam|Shia]] [[Houthis]] and forces loyal to former President [[Ali Abdullah Saleh]], who was deposed in the 2011 uprising.<ref>\"[http://edition.cnn.com/2015/03/26/middleeast/yemen-saudi-arabia-airstrikes/ Saudi-led coalition strikes rebels in Yemen, inflaming tensions in region]\". [[CNN]]. 27 March 2015.</ref> He first put together a coalition of ten [[Sunni Islam|Sunni Muslim]] countries. Code-named Operation Decisive Storm, this was the first time the [[Royal Saudi Air Force|Saudi Air Force]] had launched airstrikes against another country since the 1990\u201391 Gulf War.\n\nAccording to [[Farea Al-Muslim]], direct [[war crimes]] have been committed during the conflict; for example, an [[Internally displaced person|IDP]] camp was hit by a Saudi airstrike.<ref>{{cite web|last=Kasinof|first=Laura|title=How Yemen's Civil Conflict Turned Into a Regional Proxy War |url=http://www.thenation.com/article/206161/how-yemens-civil-conflict-turned-regional-proxy-war|work=[[The Nation]]}}</ref> [[Human Rights Watch]] (HRW) wrote that the Saudi-led air campaign had conducted airstrikes in apparent violation of the [[Law of war|laws of war]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Yemen: Saudi-Led Airstrikes Used Cluster Munitions |url=https://www.hrw.org/news/2015/05/03/yemen-saudi-led-airstrikes-used-cluster-munitions |publisher=Human Rights Watch |date=3 May 2015 }}</ref> Human rights groups have also criticized Saudi Arabia for the alleged use of cluster bombs against Yemeni civilians.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Fanack|title=A New Wind in Saudi Arabia|url=https://chronicle.fanack.com/saudi-arabia/history-past-to-present/a-new-wind-in-saudi-arabia/|website=Fanack.com|accessdate=14 July 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Crown Prince changes===\n{{multiple image|total_width=300\n|image1=Prince Mohammed bin Naif bin Abdulaziz 2013-01-16 (2).jpg\n|image2=Crown Prince Mohammad bin Salman Al Saud - 2017.jpg\n|footer= [[Muhammad bin Nayef]] in January 2013 (left); [[Mohammed bin Salman]] in May 2017\n}}\nIn April 2015, three months after becoming king, Salman appointed a full nephew, [[Muhammad bin Nayef]], as the new Crown Prince to replace his youngest brother [[Muqrin bin Abdulaziz|Prince Muqrin]]. Furthermore, he made his son, Mohammad bin Salman, the Deputy Crown Prince. Almost all powers under the king were concentrated in the hands of the crown prince and deputy crown prince, both of whom held the portfolio determining all security and economic development issues in Saudi Arabia.<ref name=\"Saudi king resets succession to cope with turbulent times\">{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-saudi-politics-idUSKBN0NK05W20150429 |title=Saudi king resets succession to cope with turbulent times |last=McDowall |first=Angus |last2=Aboudi |first2=Sami |date=29 April 2015 |editor-last=Maclean |editor-first=William |editor2-last=Fletcher |editor2-first=Philippa |editor3-last=Graff |editor3-first=Peter |agency=[[Reuters]]   |location=Riyadh |archive-url=https://archive.is/20170514195316/http://www.reuters.com/article/us-saudi-politics-idUSKBN0NK05W20150429 |archive-date=14 May 2017 |url-status=live |access-date=23 April 2016 |last3=Hashem |first3=Mostafa |last4=El Dahan |first4=Maha |last5=Shamseddine |first5=Reem |last6=Gloystein |first6=Henning |last7=Mohammed |first7=Arshad |df= }}</ref>\n\nKing Salman then removed Muhammad bin Nayef from the line of succession to the Saudi throne on 21 June 2017 and designated his son Mohammad bin Salman as the new crown prince.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aljazeera.com/news/2017/06/saudi-arabia-appoints-king-salman-son-crown-prince-170621033707437.html|title=Mohammed bin Salman named Saudi Arabia's crown prince|publisher=Al Jazeera|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170621091448/http://www.aljazeera.com/news/2017/06/saudi-arabia-appoints-king-salman-son-crown-prince-170621033707437.html|archivedate=21 June 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref> At the same time, King Salman removed Muhammad bin Nayef from his other positions in the Saudi government.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cnn.com/2017/06/21/middleeast/saudi-arabia-crown-prince/index.html|title=Saudi Arabia's king replaces nephew with son as heir to throne|author=Nicole Chavez, Tamara Qiblawi and James Griffiths|website=CNN}}</ref> Mohammad bin Salman has been described as the [[power behind the throne]].<ref>[http://www.economist.com/saudi_interview?fsrc=scn%2Ftw_ec%2Ftranscript_interview_with_muhammad_bin_salman Transcript: Interview with Muhammad bin Salman] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160109180902/http://www.economist.com/saudi_interview?fsrc=scn%2Ftw_ec%2Ftranscript_interview_with_muhammad_bin_salman|date=9 January 2016}} ''The Economist'', 6 January 2016.</ref>\n\n===KSRelief===\nIn May 2015 the King Salman Center for Relief and Humanitarian Aid (KSRelief) was established to deliver aid internationally to victims of civil war and natural disaster, working with the UN and other agencies. As of June 2018, KSRelief has implemented more than 400 individual projects in 40 countries at a cost of $1.8 billion.<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=King Salman relief center implements 428 projects worth $1.7 bln |url=https://english.alarabiya.net/en/News/gulf/2018/06/26/King-Salman-relief-center-implements-428-projects-worth-1-7-bln.html |work=[[Al Arabiya]] |location= |date=26 June 2018 |access-date=24 September 2018}}</ref> Moreover, in 2018, KSRelief assisted 180,555 Syrian patients living in [[Zaatari refugee camp|Zataari]] Syrian refugees camp in [[Jordan]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.arabnews.com/node/1430111/saudi-arabia|title=King Salman Humanitarian aid agency treats 180,000 Syrian patients in Jordan|date=2019-01-04|website=Arab News|language=en|access-date=2019-01-04}}</ref> In 2019, KSRelief signed a memorandum of cooperation with [[UNICEF]] that aims at enhancing cooperation in the humanitarian field, exchanging knowledge, sharing experiences, promoting voluntary work and boosting capacity building programs.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.arabnews.com/node/1451876/saudi-arabia|title=KSRelief inks cooperation deal with UNICEF|date=2019-02-13|website=Arab News|language=en|access-date=2019-02-18}}</ref> Until 2019, the center provided 1,839 Yemeni civilians wounded during the war with prosthetic limbs for a total amount of $2.3 million.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.arabnews.com/node/1457451/saudi-arabia|title=Saudi Arabia's relief center prosthetic limbs project benefits 1,839 Yemenis|date=2019-02-24|website=Arab News|language=en|access-date=2019-02-25}}</ref>\n\nIn its ongoing efforts to support people of Yemen, KSRelief organized a vocational training program to train women in [[Yemen]] to enable them to earn money for themselves and their families.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.arabnews.com/node/1462856/saudi-arabia|title=KSRelief launches pilot project for female breadwinners in Yemen|date=2019-03-07|website=Arab News|language=en|access-date=2019-03-07}}</ref> In a similar context, under the umbrella of the UN, KSRelief has led an international team to implement a rehabilitation project for the children affected by war in Yemen.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.arabnews.com/node/1462721/saudi-arabia|title=Saudi Arabia's aid agency takes steps to improve rehab projects|date=2019-03-06|website=Arab News|language=en|access-date=2019-03-07}}</ref> Moreover, as part of the 40th session of the UN Human Rights' Council, KSRelief organized an event entitled: Children and the Humanitarian Crisis in Yemen where it presented a number of facts and figures related to the amount of assistance provided by the center to the people of Yemen. This includes the implementation of 328 projects for an amount of $2 billion.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.spa.gov.sa/viewfullstory.php?lang=en&newsid=1896914#1896914|title=KSrelief Holds Seminar on Children, Humanitarian Crisis, in Yemen, in Geneva The official Saudi Press Agency|website=www.spa.gov.sa|access-date=2019-03-13}}</ref> Furthermore, in 2018 alone KSRelief provided medical services to 2,501,897 Yemenis.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.arabnews.com/node/1478721/saudi-arabia|title=Saudi Arabia's KSRelief team discusses Yemen livelihood project|date=2019-04-07|website=Arab News|language=en|access-date=2019-04-07}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, KSrelief signed a number of agreements with different civil society organizations to implement relief projects for the benefit of Palestinian and Syrian refugees as well as the host Lebanese community. An agreement was concluded with the UNHCR to support the families affected by war for an amount of $5 million. Another one was concluded with IOM to help Syrian refugees under the poverty line for an amount of $3.8 million.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.arabnews.com/node/1487791/saudi-arabia|title=KSRelief signs agreements for relief to Lebanese, Syrians and Palestinians|date=2019-04-25|website=Arab News|language=en|access-date=2019-05-01}}</ref>\n\n=== Human rights ===\nIn February 2012, [[Ali Mohammed Baqir al-Nimr]] was arrested for participating in, and encouraging, pro-[[democracy]] protests, when he was 16 or 17 years old. In May 2014, Ali Al-Nimr was sentenced to be executed, despite the minimum age for execution being 18 when a crime is committed.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://usuncut.com/world/ali-mohammed-al-nimr-father-speaks-out/|title=Father of Ali, Saudi teen slated for public execution, speaks out}}</ref> Ali Al-Nimr has reported that he was tortured during his detention. As of 23 September 2015, the sentence awaited ratification by King Salman.<ref>Zafar Gondal, [http://www.esohr.org/en/?page_id=756 \"Analysis of court Judgment and conviction of Ali bin Mohammad bin Baqir Al-Nimr \u2013 Saudi Arabia\"], London, 15 December 2015. Retrieved 20 February 2015</ref>\n\nIn February 2015, a man from [[Hafar Al-Batin]] was sentenced to death for rejecting Islam.<ref>{{cite web | title= Saudi Arabia court gives death penalty to man who renounced his Muslim faith|url= https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/middleeast/saudiarabia/11431509/Saudi-Arabia-court-gives-death-penalty-to-man-who-renounced-his-Muslim-faith.html|work=The Daily Telegraph|date=24 February 2015 }}</ref> In June 2015, Saudi Arabia's Supreme Court upheld the sentence of 1,000 lashes and 10 years in prison for [[Raif Badawi]], a Saudi Arabian blogger who was imprisoned in 2012 after being charged for 'insulting Islam'.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-33039815|title=Saudi court upholds blogger's 10 years and 1,000 lashes|publisher=BBC|date=7 June 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Iran and Syria===\n[[File:Donald Trump and King Salman bin Abdulaziz Al Saud talk together, May 2017.jpg|thumb|US President [[Donald Trump]] with King Salman, Riyadh, 20 May 2017]]\nUS Defense Secretary [[Ashton Carter]] met with the King and his Arabian military counterpart, Deputy Crown Prince [[Mohammad bin Salman]], at Jeddah to answer regional security concerns in the Kingdom and the Gulf states over lifting Iranian economic and conventional military sanctions as the [[Joint Comprehensive Plan of Action]] outlines. The King has misgivings over the deal since it would increase the regional power of Iran especially in the proxy conflicts in Syria, Yemen, and elsewhere.<ref>Tait, Robert and Foster, Peter. (22 July 2015) \"Saudi Arabia's King Salman backs Israel over Iran nuclear deal concerns\". The Telegraph. Retrieved 22 July 2015. [https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/middleeast/saudiarabia/11756739/Saudi-Arabias-King-Salman-backs-Israel-over-Iran-nuclear-deal-concerns.html The Telegraph website]</ref> In January 2016, Saudi Arabia executed the prominent [[Shia Islam in Saudi Arabia|Saudi Shia]] cleric [[Nimr al-Nimr|Sheikh Nimr]].<ref name=\"nimr\">{{cite web | title=Saudi execution of Shia cleric sparks outrage in Middle East |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2016/jan/02/saudi-execution-of-shia-cleric-sparks-outrage-in-middle-east |work=[[The Guardian]]| date=2 January 2016}}</ref> Iran warned that the [[House of Saud]] would pay a high price for the execution of Sheikh Nimr by God's will.<ref name=\"nimr\"/>\n\nSaudi Arabia has emerged as the main group to finance and arm the rebels fighting against the [[Syria]]n government.<ref>\"[https://www.reuters.com/article/2013/05/31/us-syria-crisis-saudi-insight-idUSBRE94U0ZV20130531 Saudi edges Qatar to control Syrian rebel support]\". Reuters. 31 May 2013</ref> Saudi Arabia openly backed the [[Army of Conquest]], an umbrella rebel group that reportedly included an [[al-Qaeda]] linked [[al-Nusra Front]] and another [[Salafi jihadism|Salafi]] coalition known as [[Ahrar al-Sham]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/middle-east/syria-crisis-turkey-and-saudi-arabia-shock-western-countries-by-supporting-antiassad-jihadists-10242747.html |title=Turkey and Saudi Arabia alarm the West by backing Islamist extremists the Americans had bombed in Syria  |author=Kim Sengupta |newspaper=The Independent |date=12 May 2015}}</ref><ref>\"[http://weekly.ahram.org.eg/News/12392.aspx Gulf allies and \u2018Army of Conquest\u2019]\". ''[[Al-Ahram Weekly]]''. 28 May 2015.</ref><ref>\"[https://news.yahoo.com/army-conquest-rebel-alliance-pressures-syria-regime-090529121.html 'Army of Conquest' rebel alliance pressures Syria regime]\". Yahoo News. 28 April 2015.</ref>\n\nIn May 2019, leaders of Gulf and Arab states held two emergency summits in Mecca to present a united front to Iran.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/jun/01/saudi-king-warns-attacks-on-oil-stations-threaten-global-supply-iran Saudi king warns attacks on oil stations threaten global supply]. ''The Guardian''. 31 May 2019.</ref> Salman accused Iran of threatening global oil supplies and shipping at a meeting of Arab leaders that called on the international community to confront Tehran following attacks on shipping and rising tensions in the oil rich region.<ref>[https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2019-05-30/saudi-king-accuses-iran-of-threatening-global-maritime-traffic Saudi King Accuses Iran of Threatening Global Oil Supplies]. ''Bloomberg''. 30 May 2019.</ref> Salman said \"what the Iranian regime is doing, from intervening in regional countries\u2019 affairs and developing its nuclear program, threatening global maritime traffic and global oil supplies, is a blatant violation of the treaties and principles of the United Nations.\" He urged the international community should \"use all means to deter this regime.\"<ref>[https://www.dw.com/en/saudi-king-iran-backed-groups-threaten-global-oil-supplies/a-48997918 Saudi king: Iran-backed groups threaten global oil supplies]. ''DW''. 1 June 2019.</ref>\n\n===Panama Papers revelations===\nKing Salman has been implicated in the [[Panama Papers]] leaks, with two companies originating in the [[British Virgin Islands]] taking mortgages in excess of US$34 million to purchase property in [[central London]]. His role has not been specified.<ref name=\"telesur\">{{cite news |title=Saudi King, UAE President at the Center of the Panama Papers |url=http://www.telesurtv.net/english/news/Saudi-King-UAE-President-at-the-Center-of-the-Panama-Papers-20160404-0024.html |newspaper=[[TeleSUR]] |date=4 April 2016 }}</ref><ref>\"[http://www.middleeasteye.net/news/complete-guide-secret-dealings-middle-east-leaders-revealed-panama-papers-leak-662088930 The who's who of Middle East leaders and their secret billions]\". Middle East Eye. 4 April 2016.</ref> According to [[TeleSUR]], \"King Salman\u2019s net worth is estimated at US$17.0 billion.\"<ref name=\"telesur\"/> The then-Crown Prince Muhammad bin Nayef has also been [[List of people named in the Panama Papers|named]] in association with the Papers.<ref>\"[http://www.france24.com/en/20160404-panama-papers-politicians-named-europe-africa A world tour of the politicians named in the Panama Papers]\". [[France 24]]. 5 April 2016.</ref>\n\n===Later reforms===\nFurther government reforms took place in June 2018, when King Salman replaced the labor and Islamic affairs ministers.<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=King Salman's reign sees largest structural reforms in history of Saudi Arabia |url=https://english.alarabiya.net/en/features/2018/06/02/King-Salman-s-reign-sees-largest-structural-reforms-in-history-of-Saudi-Arabia.html |work=[[Al Arabiya]] |location= |date=2 June 2018 |access-date=24 September 2018}}</ref> The appointment as labor minister of Ahmed al-Rajhi, a businessman, signalled a growing role for private sector expertise in the Saudi government.<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=FaceOf: Ahmed bin Suleiman Al-Rajhi, new minister of labor and social development|url=http://www.arabnews.com/node/1314961/saudi-arabia |work=[[Arab News]] |location= |date=4 June 2018 |access-date=24 September 2018}}</ref> The new minister for Islamic affairs, Abdullatif al-Alsheikh, had previously been credited with reining in the power of the religious police.<ref name=FT070218>{{cite news |last=Al Omran |first=Ahmed |date=2 June 2018 |title=Saudi Arabia creates new departments in reshuffle |url=https://www.ft.com/content/1459999c-668e-11e8-b6eb-4acfcfb08c11 |work=[[Financial Times]] |location= |access-date=24 September 2018}}</ref>\n\nAt the same time King Salman ordered the establishment of a new Ministry of Culture, with responsibility for delivering Saudi Vision 2030's cultural goals; and the Council of Royal Reserves, tasked with environmental protection.<ref name=FT070218/><ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Saudi Arabia seeks ecotourism boost by protecting environment, wildlife |url=http://www.arabnews.com/node/1314391/saudi-arabia |work=[[Arab News]] |location= |date=3 June 2018 |access-date=24 September 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Influence==\n[[File:Abdel Fattah el-Sisi, King Salman of Saudi Arabia, Melania Trump, and Donald Trump, May 2017.jpg|thumb|left|Salman, US President Donald Trump, and Egyptian President [[Abdel Fattah el-Sisi]] touching a glowing orb at the [[2017 Riyadh summit]].]] \nSalman was often a mediator in settling royal conflicts among the extended Al Saud family \u2013 estimated at 4,000 princes. He was a prominent figure of the royal council, which allowed him to select which princes will be delegated which responsibilities of the Kingdom.<ref name=pbs>{{cite web|title=Prince Salman bin Abdulaziz|url=https://www.pbs.org/wnet/wideangle/episodes/the-saudi-question/whos-who-the-house-of-saud/prince-sulayman-ibn-abdul-aziz/2871/|work=PBS|accessdate=26 May 2012}}</ref>\n\nSalman and his family own a media group, including pan-Arab daily ''[[Asharq Al-Awsat]]'' and ''[[Al Eqtisadiah]]''.<ref name=wikileaks2009>{{cite web|title=Ideological and Ownership Trends in the Saudi Media|url=http://www.cablegatesearch.net/cable.php?id=09RIYADH651|work=Wikileaks|accessdate=26 May 2012|date=11 May 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130116083750/http://www.cablegatesearch.net/cable.php?id=09RIYADH651|archivedate=16 January 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=alif>{{cite web|title=9 Challenges Facing The New Crown Prince of Saudi Arabia |url=http://alifarabia.com/2011/10/30/8-challenges-facing-the-new-crown-prince-of-saudi-arabia/ |work=Alifarabia |accessdate=26 May 2012 |date=30 October 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111122012155/http://alifarabia.com/2011/10/30/8-challenges-facing-the-new-crown-prince-of-saudi-arabia/ |archivedate=22 November 2011 |df= }}</ref> Though he owns only ten percent of the [[Saudi Research and Marketing Group]] (SRMG), he is often referred by auditors as its owner.<ref name=wikileaks2009/> He reportedly controls the organization through his son [[Faisal bin Salman bin Abdulaziz Al Saud|Prince Faisal]],<ref name=wikileaks2009/> who is a former chairman of the concern.  The SRMG publishes such daily papers as ''[[Arab News]]'', ''[[Asharq Al-Awsat]]'' and ''[[Al Eqtisadiah]]'' through its subsidiary Saudi Research and Publishing Company (SRPC).<ref>{{cite web|title=Al-Faiz new editor in chief of Arab News|url=http://www.srpc.com/en/node/44|work=SRPC|accessdate=30 April 2012}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Vladimir Putin and Salman of Saudi Arabia (2017-10-05) 1.jpg|thumb|King Salman with Russian President Vladimir Putin, [[Moscow]], 5 October 2017]]\nIn a similar vein, Salman is reported to have some strong alliances with significant journalists. He is said to be close to [[Al Arabiya]] TV director and ''[[Asharq Al-Awsat]]'' journalist Abdelrahman Al Rashid and to [[Othman Al Omeir]], who launched and is the owner of the liberal e-newspaper ''[[Elaph]]''. King Salman is thought to have connections with the ''Elaph'' website.<ref>{{cite web|title=Saudi succession issues|url=http://www.gsn-online.com/SSIs/SAMPLES/documents/GSN845.pdf|work=GSN (Gulf States Newsletter)|accessdate=13 April 2012|date=16 January 2009}}{{dead link|date=January 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n==Views==\nSalman holds traditional views with regards to political reforms and social change.<ref>{{cite web|title=Before he was king, Salman was the family disciplinarian who put princes behind bars|last=Sullivan|first=Kevin|date=23 January 2015|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/salman-is-known-for-mediating-saudi-royal-disputes/2015/01/22/1bc8dc1a-a2b0-11e4-b146-577832eafcb4_story.html|work=[[The Washington Post]]|accessdate= 25 January 2015}}</ref> In November 2002, in reference to charitable organizations accused of terrorism (e.g. [[al-Haramain Foundation]], [[Saudi High Commission for Relief of Bosnia and Herzegovina]]), he stated that he had personally taken part in the activities of such organizations,<ref name=charbris/> but added \"I know the assistance goes to doing good. But if there are those who change some work of charity into evil activities, then it is not the Kingdom's responsibility, nor its people, which helps its Arab and Muslim brothers around the world.\"<ref name=charbris>{{cite web|last=Brisard |first=Jean Charles |title=Terrorism financing. Roots and trends of Saudi terrorism financing |url=http://apgml.org/frameworks/docs/7/TF-Saudi%20financing%20Nov2002%20-%20UN%20Security%20Council.pdf |work=the Security Council, United Nations |accessdate=15 April 2012 |date=19 December 2002 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120321141344/http://www.apgml.org/frameworks/docs/7/TF-Saudi%20financing%20Nov2002%20-%20UN%20Security%20Council.pdf |archivedate=21 March 2012 |df= }}</ref>\n\n[[Al Jazeera English|Al Jazeera]] referred to Salman's views reported in a 2007 [[Contents of the United States diplomatic cables leak (Saudi Arabia)|US diplomatic cable]].<ref name=aljaz1612>{{cite news|last=Carlstrom|first=Gregg|title=Nayef's conservative policies to outlive him|url=http://www.aljazeera.com/indepth/features/2012/06/2012616185546905427.html|accessdate=17 June 2012|publisher=Al Jazeera|date=16 June 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"07RIYADH651\">{{cite document|last=Gfoeller|first=Michael|title=Ambassador's farewell call on Riyadh Provincial Governor Prince Sulayman|id={{WikiLeaks cable|07RIYADH651}}|work=WikiLeaks|date=1 April 2007|url=http://wikileaks.ch/cable/2007/04/07RIYADH651.html|accessdate=1 January 2015|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6VFK1C3dS|archivedate=1 January 2015|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Salman said that \"the pace and extent of reforms depend on social and cultural factors, ... that for social reasons\u2014not [religious] reasons\u2014reforms cannot be imposed by the [Saudi government] or there will be negative reactions, ... [and] that changes have to be introduced in a sensitive and timely manner.\" According to the cable, he said that \"democracy should not be imposed\" in Saudi Arabia, since the country \"is composed of tribes and regions and if democracy were imposed, each tribe and region would have its political party.\"<ref name=\"07RIYADH651\"/>\n\n==Personal life==\n[[File:Salman bin Abdullaziz Al Saud in his Youth.jpg|thumbnail|left|Salman in his youth]]\n\nSalman bin Abdulaziz has been married three times.<ref name=arabt18jun>{{cite news|title=Prince Sulayman Named Saudi 'Crown Prince'|url=http://www.arabtimesonline.com/NewsDetails/tabid/96/smid/414/ArticleID/184632/reftab/96/Default.aspx|accessdate=26 February 2013|work=Arab Times|date=18 June 2012|location=Riyadh}}</ref> {{As of|2017}}, he had thirteen children.<ref>{{cite web | title = Who is Mohammed bin Salman, the 31-year-old future king of Saudi Arabia? | last = Sanchez | first = Raf  | work = The Telegraph | date = 21 June 2017 | accessdate = 12 January 2018 | url = https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2017/06/21/mohammed-bin-salman-31-year-old-future-king-saudi-arabia/ }}</ref> His first wife was Sultana bint Turki Al Sudairi,<ref name=erguard>{{cite news|title=Princess Sultana|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=-PRVAAAAIBAJ&sjid=M-IDAAAAIBAJ&pg=6528,4734357&dq=king+fahd%27s+wife&hl=en|accessdate=9 February 2013|newspaper=Eugene Register Guard|date=19 June 1983}}</ref> who died aged 71 in late-July 2011.<ref name=saugaz3811/><ref>{{cite news|author=David D. Kirkpatrick|title=Surprising Saudi Rises as a Prince Among Princes|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/06/07/world/middleeast/surprising-saudi-rises-as-a-prince-among-princes.html|accessdate=29 October 2015|work=The New York Times|date=6 June 2015|location=Riyadh}}</ref> She was a first cousin of Salman, being a daughter of his maternal uncle Turki bin Ahmad Al Sudairi,<ref name=saugaz3811>{{cite news|title=Sultana, wife of Riyadh Emir, passes away |url=http://www.saudigazette.com.sa/index.cfm?method=home.regcon&contentID=20110803106640 |accessdate=26 May 2012 |newspaper=Saudi Gazette |date=3 August 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131228132942/http://www.saudigazette.com.sa/index.cfm?method=home.regcon&contentID=20110803106640 |archivedate=28 December 2013 |df= }}</ref> who was a former governor of the [[Asir Province]].<ref name=datsultana>{{cite web|title=Sultana bint Ahmad bin Muhammad al Sudairi|url=http://www.datarabia.com/royals/viewBio.do?id=176248|work=Datarabia|accessdate=8 May 2012}}</ref> Sultana Al Sudairi supported the Prince Fahd bin Salman Charitable Society for the Care of Kidney Patients and other charitable organizations in the country.<ref name=siasat2011/> His children from this marriage are [[Fahd bin Salman bin Abdulaziz Al Saud|Prince Fahd]] (died 2001), [[Sultan bin Salman Al Saud|Prince Sultan]], [[Ahmed bin Salman bin Abdulaziz Al Saud|Prince Ahmed]] (died 2002), [[Abdulaziz bin Salman Al Saud|Prince Abdulaziz]], [[Faisal bin Salman bin Abdulaziz Al Saud|Prince Faisal]] and [[Hassa bint Salman Al Saud|Princess Hassa]].<ref name=siasat2011>{{cite news|title=Kingdom mourns loss of princess|url=http://www.siasat.com/english/news/kingdom-mourns-loss-princess|accessdate=26 May 2012|newspaper=The Siasat Daily|date=3 August 2011}}</ref>\n\nHis eldest son, Fahd bin Salman, died of [[heart failure]] aged 47 in July 2001.<ref name=tt25jul>{{cite news|title=Death of a Generous man|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/horseracing/3009518/Death-of-a-Generous-man.html|accessdate=3 March 2013|newspaper=The Telegraph|date=25 July 2001}}</ref> His third son, Ahmad bin Salman, died after a [[heart attack]] in July 2002 aged 43.<ref name=usatoday>{{cite news|last=Bradley|first=John R.|title=Prince Ahmed's cousin killed on way to funeral|url=https://www.usatoday.com/sports/horses/stories/2002-07-23-sulayman-funeral_x.htm|accessdate=26 May 2012|newspaper=USA Today|date=23 July 2002}}</ref> Sultan bin Salman became the first person of royal blood, the first-ever [[Arab]], and the first [[Muslim]] to fly in outer space when he flew aboard the [[Space Shuttle Discovery]] ([[STS-51-G]]) in June 1985.<ref name=wstar20jun>{{cite news|title=First Arab astronaut makes a royal tour of space|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=0lg_AAAAIBAJ&sjid=AlMMAAAAIBAJ&pg=990,942020&dq=sulayman+bin+abdulaziz&hl=en|accessdate=3 March 2013|newspaper=The Windsor Star|date=20 June 1985|location=New York|pages=B12}}</ref> Sultan bin Salman is currently the chairman of the Saudi Space Commission.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ssc.gov.sa/index-en.html#about|title=Saudi Space Commission|website=ssc.gov.sa|access-date=2020-03-13}}</ref> Prince Sultan bin Salman was formerly the chairman of the [[Saudi Commission for Tourism & Antiquities]] (SCTA), which later was changed to be the ministry of Tourism.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mt.gov.sa/en/AboutSCTA/Pages/President.aspx|title=Curriculum Vitae|website=mt.gov.sa|access-date=2020-03-13}}</ref> Abdulaziz bin Salman has been the deputy minister of oil since 1995, then the minister of Energy since 2019 <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/saudi-arabia-names-new-energy-minister-11567895724|title=Saudi Arabia Names New Energy Minister|last=Faucon|first=Summer Said, Jared Malsin and Benoit|website=WSJ|language=en-US|access-date=2019-11-25}}</ref><ref name=wikileaks2008>{{cite web|title=Saudi oil assistance to Pakistan proceeding slowly|url=http://www.cablegatesearch.net/cable.php?id=08RIYADH1175|work=Wikileaks|accessdate=26 May 2012|date=30 July 2008|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120526092120/http://cablegatesearch.net/cable.php?id=08RIYADH1175|archivedate=26 May 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Faisal bin Salman is the governor of [[Al Madinah Province|Madinah province]].\n\nHis child from his second marriage with Sarah bint Faisal Al Subai'ai (divorced) is [[Saud Bin Salman bin Abdulaziz al Saud|Prince Saud]]. His children from his third marriage with Fahda bint Falah bin Sultan Al Hathleen<ref>{{cite news|author1=Hugh Miles|title=Saudi Arabia: Eight of King Salman's 11 surviving brothers want to oust him|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/middle-east/saudi-arabia-power-struggle-between-king-salman-and-mohammed-bin-salman-could-bring-down-the-a6706801.html|accessdate=22 April 2016|work=Independent|date=23 October 2015}}</ref> are [[Mohammad bin Salman|Prince Mohammed]], [[Turki bin Salman Al Saud|Prince Turki]], [[Khalid bin Salman bin Abdulaziz Al Saud|Prince Khalid]], Prince Nayif, Prince Bandar, and Prince Rakan.<ref>{{cite web|title=Family Tree of Salman bin Abdulaziz bin Abdul Rahman Al Saud|url=http://www.datarabia.com/royals/famtree.do?id=176822|work=Datarabia|accessdate=1 May 2012}}</ref>\n\nPrince Mohammad was his private adviser at the Ministry of Defense and at the Crown Prince Court.<ref>{{cite news|title=Prince Sultan arrives to Bahrain to attend Bahrain Grand Prix|url=http://www.bna.bh/portal/en/news/505092|accessdate=23 April 2012|agency=Bahrain News Agency|date=22 April 2012}}</ref> Mohammad was appointed as the Minister of Defense and head of the royal court upon his father's accession to the throne in January 2015.<ref>{{cite news|title=Saudi Prince Mohammad bin Salman named defense minister|url=http://english.alarabiya.net/en/News/middle-east/2015/01/23/Saudi-Prince-Mohammad-bin-Salman-appointed-defense-minister-head-of-Royal-Court.html|accessdate=23 January 2015|publisher=Al Arabiya|date=23 January 2015}}</ref> Turki bin Salman became the chairman of the [[Saudi Research and Marketing Group]] in February 2013, replacing his elder brother Faisal bin Salman.<ref name=anews13>{{cite news|title=Prince Turki succeeds Prince Faisal as SRMG chairman|url=http://www.arabnews.com/saudi-arabia/prince-turki-succeeds-prince-faisal-srmg-chairman|accessdate=9 February 2013|newspaper=Arab News|date=9 February 2013}}</ref>\n\nSalman was the closest brother to [[Sultan bin Abdulaziz|Crown Prince Sultan]], having remained at his side during his constant illness and recovery in [[New York City|New York]] and [[Morocco]], from 2008-11.<ref name=alakhbar>{{cite news|last=al Baker |first=Basheer |title=Prince Sulayman Seeks Balance in Saudi Transitional Period |url=http://english.al-akhbar.com/content/prince-sulayman-seeks-balance-saudi-transitional-period |accessdate=23 April 2012 |newspaper=Al Akhbar |date=3 November 2011 }}{{dead link|date=April 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Prince Sultan described him as \"the prince of loyalty\" in a letter sent to him.<ref name=letter>{{cite news|title=Late crown prince's letter shows his deep love toward Sulayman|url=http://www.arabnews.com/node/402044|accessdate=29 July 2012|newspaper=Arab News|date=26 December 2011}}</ref> Salman was also [[Fahd of Saudi Arabia|King Fahd]]'s most trusted adviser during his reign.<ref name=iasps>{{cite journal|last=Wihbey|first=Paul Michael|title=Succession in Saudi Arabia: The not so silent struggle|journal=IASPS Research Papers in Strategy|year=1997|issue=4|url=http://www.iasps.org/strategic4/SA.htm|accessdate=14 May 2012}}</ref><ref name=mvio>{{cite journal|last=Viorst|first=Milton|title=The storm and the citadel|journal=Foreign Affairs|date=January\u2013February 1996|volume=75|issue=1|pages=93\u2013107|url=http://www.foreignaffairs.com/articles/51625/milton-viorst/the-storm-and-the-citadel|accessdate=1 June 2012|doi=10.2307/20047470|jstor=20047470}}</ref>\n\nHis legal counsel was William Jeffress, Jr., of US-based firm, [[Baker Botts|Baker Botts LLP]], in a lawsuit filed by families of victims of the [[September 11th terrorist attacks|11 September terrorist attacks]] from 2002-10.<ref>{{cite web|title=Representative Engagements|url=http://www.bakerbotts.com/william-h-jeffress/|publisher=Baker Botts L.L.P.|accessdate=7 June 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120805115906/http://www.bakerbotts.com/william-h-jeffress/|archivedate=5 August 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2010, Salman underwent [[spinal surgery]] in the [[United States]] and remained out of the kingdom for recovery.<ref name=ginm>{{cite news|title=King Sulayman bin Abdulaziz undergone successful surgery, Royal Court statement says|url=http://www.gulfinthemedia.com/index.php?m=gcc_press&id=2271052&cnt=171&lang=en&PHPSESSID=6ae1931c79dcdc291ac1f3b9d2d1e5fb|accessdate=26 May 2012|work=Gulf in the Media|date=17 August 2010}}</ref> He has had one [[stroke]] and despite receiving physiotherapy; his left arm does not work as well as his right.<ref>{{cite web|last=Henderson|first=Simon|title=The Man Who Would Be King|url=https://foreignpolicy.com/articles/2012/04/10/the_man_who_would_be_king|work=Foreign Policy|accessdate=12 April 2012|date=10 April 2012}}</ref><ref name=hen10jan>{{cite news|last=Henderson|first=Simon|title=To Stop Iran, Get a New Saudi King|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/international/archive/2013/01/to-stop-iran-get-a-new-saudi-king/267013/|accessdate=19 April 2013|newspaper=The Atlantic|date=10 January 2013}}</ref><ref>[https://www.economist.com/news/middle-east-and-africa/21600180-king-abdullah-appoints-second-line-throne-next-after-next Next after next\u2026] ''The Economist'' (Cairo). 5 April 2014. Retrieved 4 August 2014.</ref> Salman also suffers from mild [[dementia]],<ref>{{cite news|author=David Ignatius|title=A 30-year-old Saudi prince could jump-start the kingdom \u2014 or drive it off a cliff|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/global-opinions/a-30-year-old-saudi-prince-could-jump-start-the-kingdom--or-drive-it-off-a-cliff/2016/06/28/ce669a3e-3c69-11e6-a66f-aa6c1883b6b1_story.html|accessdate=20 May 2016|work=The Washington Post|date=28 June 2016}}</ref> specifically [[Alzheimer's disease|Alzheimer's]].<ref name=\"A family revolt could bring down the Saudi monarchy\">{{cite news|last1=Miles|first1=Hugh|title=A family revolt could bring down the Saudi monarchy|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/middle-east/saudi-arabia-power-struggle-between-king-salman-and-mohammed-bin-salman-could-bring-down-the-a6706801.html|accessdate=21 September 2016|date=23 October 2015}}</ref>\n\nUS intelligence officials believe that King Salman has been kept apart from his wife Princess Fahda bint Falah Al Hathleen for several years, on the orders of their son Prince Mohammad bin Salman.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/world/u-s-officials-saudi-crown-prince-has-hidden-his-mother-n847391 |title=U.S. officials: Saudi crown prince has hidden his mother from his father, the king |publisher=Nbcnews.com |date= |accessdate=2018-06-27}}</ref> He was reportedly concerned that she opposed his plans for a power grab that could divide the royal family, and might have tried to prevent it. The officials interviewed said the prince placed his mother under [[house arrest]] without the king's knowledge.\n\nSalman received the Lifetime Achievement Award of the Al-Turath Charity Foundation in the field of urban heritage in 2013.<ref name=nbhf>{{cite web|title=Crown Prince receives Lifetime Achievement Award in the field of Urban Heritage|url=http://www.nbhf.org.sa/english/LatestNews.aspx?id=965|work=National Built Heritage Forum|access-date=17 July 2013}}</ref> In 2017, Salman pledged US$15,000,000 for [[Rohingya people|Rohingya Muslim]] refugees in [[Bangladesh]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://world.einnews.com/article__detail/country/saudiarabia/404985252-saudi-arabia-pledges-15-million-to-aid-rohingya-muslims-in-myanmar?vcode=PqS0|title=Saudi Arabia Pledges $15 Million to Aid Rohingya Muslims in Myanmar|first=EIN|last=News|date=20 September 2017|website=einnews.com}}</ref>\n\n==Titles, Styles and Honours==\n\n===Titles and Styles===\n*31 December 1935 - 18 June 2012: ''His Royal Highness'' Prince Salman bin Abdulaziz\n*18 June 2012 - 23 January 2015: ''His Royal Highness'' The Crown Prince of Saudi Arabia\n*23 January 2015 \u2013 present: ''Custodian of the Two Holy Mosques'' The King of Saudi Arabia\n** In diplomatic parlance: ''His Majesty'' The King of Saudi Arabia\n\n===Foreign honour===\n* {{flagu|Bahrain}} : \n** Collar of the Order of Isa bin Salman Al Khalifa (2016)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gdnonline.com/Details/148451/In-Pictures-Saudi-King-Salman-begins-official-visit-to-Bahrain/168470|title=Saudi King Salman begins official visit to Bahrain}}</ref>\n* {{flagu|Bangladesh}} : \n** Collar of the Order of the Republic (2018)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://english.alarabiya.net/en/News/gulf/2018/10/17/King-Salman-receives-Bangladesh-PM-holds-luncheon-honoring-her.html|title=Saudi King Salman receives Bangladesh PM, holds lunch in her honor}}</ref>\n* {{flagu|Brunei}} : \n** [[List of post-nominal letters (Brunei)|Royal Family Order of the Crown of Brunei]] (D.K.M.B.) (2017) <ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.pelitabrunei.gov.bn/Lists/Berita/NewDisplayForm.aspx?ID=807 |title=Berkenan menerima kunjungan muhibah Kebawah DYMM Raja Salman bin Abdulaziz Al-Saud |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=4 March 2017 |website=[[Pelita Brunei]] |language=Malay |access-date=23 February 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190204015226/http://www.pelitabrunei.gov.bn/Lists/Berita/NewDisplayForm.aspx?ID=807 |archive-date=4 February 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n* {{flagu|Djibouti}} : \n** Grand Cordon of the Order of National Star of Djibouti (2015)<ref>{{cite web|url=King Salman holds talks with Djibouti leader|title=King Salman holds talks with Djibouti leader}}</ref>\n* {{flagu|Egypt}} : \n** Collar of the [[Order of the Nile]] (2016)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://english.ahram.org.eg/NewsAFCON/2017/199078.aspx|title=Egypt's Sisi awards Saudi King Salman 'Order of the Nile' honour}}</ref>\n* {{flagu|Guinea}} : \n** Grand Cordon of the National Order of Merit (2015)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.arabnews.com/featured/news/898451|title=Top Guinea medal for King}}</ref>\n* {{flagu|Indonesia}} : \n** [[Star of the Republic of Indonesia]], 1st class (2017)<ref>{{cite web\n|url=http://english.astroawani.com/world-news/saudi-king-salman-increases-indonesias-haj-quota-134249|title=Saudi King Salman increases Indonesia's haj quota}}</ref>\n* {{flagu|Japan}} : \n** Grand Cordon of the [[Order of the Chrysanthemum]] (2017)<ref>{{cite web\n|url=http://www.arabnews.com/node/1067571/saudi-arabia|title=King Salman to hold talks with Japanese premier today}}</ref>\n* {{flagu|Jordan}} : \n** Collar of the [[Order of Al-Hussein bin Ali]] (2017)<ref>{{cite web\n|url=https://english.alarabiya.net/en/News/gulf/2017/03/28/King-Salman-holds-the-highest-award-in-Jordan.html\n|title=Saudi Arabia's King Salman receives Jordan's highest award}}</ref>\n* {{flagu|Kuwait}} : \n** Collar of the [[Order of Kuwait]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://saudigazette.com.sa/article/168929|title=Kuwaiti Crown Prince hosts banquet in honor of King Salman}}</ref>\n* {{flagu|Malaysia}} : \n** Honorary Commander of the [[Order of the Defender of the Realm#Commander|Order of the Defender of the Realm]] (P.M.N.) (1982)<ref name=\"istiadat.gov.my\">{{cite web\n|url=http://www.istiadat.gov.my/index.php/component/semakanlantikanskp/|title=Semakan Penerima Darjah Kebesaran, Bintang dan Pingat}}</ref>\n** [[Order of the Crown of the Realm|The Most Exalted Order of the Crown of the Realm]] (D.M.N.) (2017)<ref name=\"istiadat.gov.my\"/>\n* {{flagu|Mexico}} : \n** Collar of the [[Order of the Aztec Eagle]] (2016)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.arabnews.com/featured/news/866441|title=Mexico eyes Gulf investment funds}}</ref>\n* {{flagu|Morocco}} : \n** Grand Cordon of the [[Order of Ouissam Alaouite]] (1987)<ref name=\"bilateralchamber.org\">{{cite web\n|url=http://bilateralchamber.org/new-king-saudi-arabia-h-e-king-salman-bin-abdulaziz-al-saud/|title=A New King for Saudi Arabia: H.E. King Salman bin Abdulaziz Al Saud}}</ref>\n** Collar of the [[Order of Muhammad]] (2016)<ref>{{cite web\n|url=https://www.moroccoworldnews.com/2016/07/191351/saudi-arabias-king-salman-arrives-in-morocco/|title=Saudi Arabia's King Salman Arrives in Morocco}}</ref>\n* {{flagu|Niger}} : \n** Grand Commander of the [[Order of the Niger]] (2015)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.arabnews.com/saudi-arabia/news/745281|title=King Salman, Niger president discuss ties}}</ref>\n* {{flagu|Pakistan}} : \n** First Class of the [[Nishan-e-Pakistan]] (2015)<ref>{{cite web\n|url=https://www.dawn.com/news/1167300/nawaz-sharif-holds-talks-with-saudi-king-salman/|title=Nawaz Sharif holds talks with Saudi King Salman}}</ref>\n* {{flagu|Palestine}} : \n** [[Grand Collar of the State of Palestine]] (2015)<ref>{{cite web\n|url=http://www.zimbio.com/photos/Mahmoud+Abbas/King+Salman+bin+Abdul+Aziz+Al+Saud/Weekly+Bucket+Dec+28+Jan+3/oxwk3TIgdH5|title=Mahmoud Abbas and King Salman bin Abdul Aziz Al Saud}}</ref>\n* {{flagu|Senegal}} : \n** Grand Cordon of the National Order of Merit (1999)<ref name=\"bilateralchamber.org\"/>\n** Grand Cross of the Lion's National Order (2015)<ref>{{cite web\n|url=http://xalimasn.com/photos-macky-sall-recu-et-decore-par-le-roi-salman-darabie-saoudite/|title=Macky Sall re\u00e7u et d\u00e9cor\u00e9 par le Roi Salman d'Arabie Saoudite}}</ref>\n* {{flagu|Sierra Leone}} : \n** Collar of the [[Order of the Republic (Sierra Leone)]] (2017)<ref>{{cite web\n|url=http://www.albiladdailyeng.com/king-salman-awarded-medal-of-honor/|title=King Salman awarded medal of honor}}</ref>\n* {{flagu|South Africa}} : \n** Grand Cross of the [[Order of Good Hope]] (2016)<ref>{{cite web\n|url=http://www.eurasiareview.com/28032016-saudi-arabias-king-salman-holds-official-talks-with-south-africas-zuma/|title=Saudi Arabia's King Salman Holds Official Talks With South Africa's Zuma}}</ref>\n* {{flagu|Spain}} : \n** Grand Cross of the [[Order of Civil Merit]]<ref>{{cite web\n|url=https://www.boe.es/boe/dias/1974/02/27/pdfs/A04034-04034.pdf/|title=Otras disposiciones}}</ref>\n* {{flagu|Tunisia}} : \n** Grand Cordon of the [[Order of the Republic (Tunisia)|Order of the Republic]] of Tunisia (2019)<ref>{{cite web\n|url=http://saudigazette.com.sa/article/562285/SAUDI-ARABIA/King-Salman-Tunisian-president-hold-talks-oversee-signing-of-two-deals-confer-medals/|title=King Salman, Tunisian president hold talks, oversee signing of two deals & confer medals}}</ref>\n* {{flagu|Turkey}} : \n** Collar of the [[Order of the Republic (Turkey)]] (2016)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.arabia-saudita.it/news.php?id=439|title=Colloqui ufficiali tra il Custode delle Due Sacre Moschee e il Presidente Erdogan, nel corso della visita di Stato di Re Salman in Turchia}}</ref>\n* {{flagu|Yemen}} : \n** Grand Cordon of the Order of the Republic (2001)<ref name=\"bilateralchamber.org\"/>\n* {{flagu|UAE}} : \n** Collar of the [[Order of Zayed]] (2016)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.arabnews.com/node/1018961/saudi-arabia|title=King starts Gulf tour with UAE visit}}</ref>\n* {{flagu|Ukraine}} : \n** Collar of the [[Order of Prince Yaroslav the Wise]] (2017)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.arabnews.com/node/1186921/saudi-arabia|title=Riyadh, Kiev cement relations with President Poroshenko's Saudi visit}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Succession to the Saudi Arabian throne]]\n* [[List of rulers of Saudi Arabia]]\n* [[List of things named after Saudi Kings]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Salman of Saudi Arabia}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20150127015359/http://midwestdiplomacy.com/2013/11/17/shifting-sands-and-the-gulf-monarchies/ \"Shifting Sands and the Gulf\" on Sulayman's transition as King]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20150520015551/http://houseofsaud.com/profiles/royal-lineage/salman-bin-abdulaziz-al-saud/ \"King Salman Royal Profile\" by Royal Families of the World]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-hou|[[House of Saud]]|31 December|1935|Living|name=Salman}}\n{{s-reg}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Abdullah of Saudi Arabia|Abdullah]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[King of Saudi Arabia]]|years=2015\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc|heir=[[Mohammad bin Salman]]|heir-type=Heir apparent}}\n|-\n{{s-roy|sa}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Nayef bin Abdulaziz|Nayef]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Crown Prince of Saudi Arabia]]|years=2012\u20132015}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Muqrin bin Abdulaziz Al Saud|Muqrin]]}}\n|-\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=Abdullah}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Prime Minister of Saudi Arabia]]|years=2015\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Badr bin Saud bin Abdulaziz Al Saud|Badr bin Saud bin Abdulaziz]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Governor of [[Riyadh Region]]|years=1963\u20132011}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Sattam bin Abdulaziz Al Saud|Sattam bin Abdulaziz]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Sultan bin Abdulaziz Al Saud]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Armed Forces of Saudi Arabia|Minister of Defense]]|years=2011\u20132015}}\n{{s-aft|after=Mohammad bin Salman}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{SaudiKings}}\n{{Current sovereigns}}\n{{Saudi Crown Princes}}\n{{Sons of Ibn Saud}}\n{{Arab country leaders}}\n{{List of Current Heads of State of G20}}\n{{Current G20 Leaders}}\n{{Current OPEC leaders}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:1935 births]]\n[[Category:Governors of Riyadh Province]]\n[[Category:Kings of Saudi Arabia]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Prime Ministers of Saudi Arabia]]\n[[Category:Sons of Ibn Saud|Salman]]\n[[Category:Grand Cross of the Order of Civil Merit]]\n[[Category:People named in the Panama Papers]]\n[[Category:Custodian of the Two Holy Mosques]]\n[[Category:Crown Princes of Saudi Arabia]]\n[[Category:Honorary Recipients of the Order of the Crown of the Realm]]\n[[Category:Collars of the Order of Mubarak the Great]]\n[[Category:Collars of the Order of the Aztec Eagle]]\n[[Category:Honorary Commanders of the Order of the Defender of the Realm]]\n[[Category:Grand Cordons of the Order of the Nile]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of al-Hussein bin Ali]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of Prince Yaroslav the Wise, 1st class]]\n[[Category:Saudi Arabian billionaires]]\n", "text_old": "{{redirect-distinguish|King Salman|King Solomon|King Salmon (disambiguation){{!}}King Salmon}}\n{{short description|King of Saudi Arabia}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2017}}\n{{POV|date=August 2019}}\n{{Infobox royalty\n|name        = Salman bin Abdulaziz Al Saud\n|image       = Salman of Saudi Arabia - 2020 (49563590728) (cropped).jpg\n|caption     = Salman bin Abdulaziz Al Saud in February 2020\n|succession  = {{plainlist|\n*[[King of Saudi Arabia]]\n*[[Prime Minister of Saudi Arabia]]\n*[[Custodian of the Two Holy Mosques]]}}\n|reign       = 23 January 2015 \u2013 present\n|coronation  = 23 January 2015 \n|cor-type    = [[Bay'ah]]\n|predecessor = [[Abdullah of Saudi Arabia|Abdullah]]\n|successor   = {{plainlist|\n*[[Muqrin bin Abdulaziz]] (2015)\n*[[Muhammad bin Nayef]] (2015&ndash;17)\n*[[Mohammad bin Salman]] (2017&ndash;present)}}\n|suc-type    = {{nowrap|Heir apparent}}\n|birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1935|12|31|df=y}}\n|birth_place = [[Riyadh]], [[Saudi Arabia]]\n|issue       ={{Collapsible list|[[Fahd bin Salman bin Abdulaziz Al Saud|Fahd]]|\n[[Sultan bin Salman Al Saud|Sultan]]|\n[[Ahmed bin Salman bin Abdulaziz Al Saud|Ahmed]]|\n[[Abdulaziz bin Salman Al Saud|Abdulaziz]]|\n[[Faisal bin Salman bin Abdulaziz Al Saud|Faisal]]|\n[[Hassa bint Salman Al Saud|Hassa]]|\n[[Saud Bin Salman bin Abdulaziz al Saud|Saud]]|\n[[Mohammad bin Salman|Mohammad]]|\n[[Turki bin Salman Al Saud|Turki]]|\n[[Khalid bin Salman bin Abdulaziz Al Saud|Khalid]]|\nNayif|\nBandar|\nRakan}}\n|issue-link  = #Personal life\n|full name   = Salman bin Abdulaziz bin Abdul Rahman bin Faisal bin Turki bin Abdullah bin Mohammed bin Saud\n|house       = [[House of Saud]]\n|father      = [[Ibn Saud]]\n|mother      = [[Hassa bint Ahmed Al Sudairi|Hassa bint Ahmad Al Sudairi]]\n|signature   =\n|spouse = {{plainlist|\n*Sultana bint Turki Al Sudairi (deceased in 2011)\n*Sarah bint Faisal Al Subai'ai (divorced)\n*Fahda bint Falah Al Sultan}}\n}}\n\n'''Salman bin Abdulaziz Al Saud''' ({{lang-ar|\u0633\u0644\u0645\u0627\u0646 \u0628\u0646 \u0639\u0628\u062f \u0627\u0644\u0639\u0632\u06cc\u0632 \u0622\u0644 \u0633\u0639\u0648\u062f}} ''{{transl|ar|ALA|Salm\u0101n ibn \u2018Abd al-\u2018Az\u012bz \u0100l Su\u2018\u016bd}}'', <small>[[Najdi Arabic]] pronunciation:</small> {{IPA-ar|s\u00e6l\u02c8m\u00e6\u02d0n ben \u02c8\u02a2\u00e6bd \u00e6l\u02a2\u00e6\u02c8zi\u02d0z \u0294\u00e6\u02d0l s\u00e6\u02c8\u02a2u\u02d0d|}}; born 31 December 1935) has been the [[King of Saudi Arabia|king]] and [[Prime Minister of Saudi Arabia|prime minister]] of [[Saudi Arabia]] and [[custodian of the Two Holy Mosques]] since 23 January 2015.\n\nHe was the deputy governor of [[Riyadh Province|Riyadh]] and later the governor of Riyadh for 48 years from 1963 to 2011. He was then appointed minister of Defense. He was also named the [[Crown Prince of Saudi Arabia|crown prince]] in 2012 following the death of his brother [[Nayef bin Abdulaziz]]. Salman became the new king of Saudi Arabia on 23 January 2015 following the death of his half-brother, [[Abdullah of Saudi Arabia|King Abdullah]]. Since 2019 he is also the oldest surviving son of [[Ibn Saud]].\n\nHis major initiatives as king include the [[Operation Decisive Storm|Saudi intervention]] in the [[Yemeni Civil War (2015\u2013present)|Yemeni Civil War]], [[Saudi Vision 2030]], and a 2017 decree allowing Saudi women to drive. His son, Crown Prince [[Mohammad bin Salman]], is considered the ''de facto'' ruler of Saudi Arabia and has led many reforms within the country, as well as engendering a number of controversies, including the [[2017\u201319 Saudi Arabian purge|2017 arrest of members of the Saudi royal family]] and the [[killing of Jamal Khashoggi]]. \n\n==Early life==\nSalman was born on 31 December 1935, and is reported to be the 25th son of [[Ibn Saud]], the first monarch and founder of Saudi Arabia.<ref name=\"Aawsat\"/> Salman and his six full brothers make up the [[Sudairi Seven]].<ref name=thedip12>{{cite journal|title=An Heir to the Kingdom: New Crown Prince Salman|journal=The Diplomat|date=July\u2013August 2012|volume=35|pages=8\u201311|url=http://www.ids.gov.sa/sites/ar/Diplomat/Book%20Diplomat%2035.pdf|accessdate=9 February 2013}}</ref><ref>Alexander Bligh. From Prince to King; Succession to the throne in Saudi Arabia. New York, New York University Press (1984). Arabic edition: Alexander Bligh. Min amir ila malik. London, D.A. Publications (1989).</ref> He was raised in the [[Murabba Palace]].<ref name=nbhf/>\n\nSalman received his early education at the [[Princes' School]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Arab Rulers' Academic Degrees, Majors at a Glance|url=https://ifpnews.com/exclusive/arab-rulers-academic-degrees/|accessdate=20 January 2019}}</ref> in the capital city of [[Riyadh]], a school established by Ibn Saud specifically to provide education for his children.<ref name=moi>{{cite web|title=His royal highness Prince Salman bin Abdulaziz|url=http://www.riyadh.gov.sa/en/Pages/Princes/Princes.aspx?ItemId=5|work=Ministry of Interior|accessdate=12 May 2012|url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130930121212/http://www.riyadh.gov.sa/en/Pages/Princes/Princes.aspx?ItemId=5 |archivedate=30 September 2013}}</ref> He studied religion and modern science.<ref name=sew1>{{cite web|title=Ministers with portfolio|url=http://www.saudiembassy.net/print/about/Biographies-of-Ministers.aspx|work=Saudi Embassy, Washington DC|accessdate=19 June 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120607004102/http://www.saudiembassy.net/print/about/Biographies-of-Ministers.aspx|archivedate=7 June 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Governor of Riyadh==\n[[File:Vladimir Putin in Saudi Arabia 11-12 February 2007-14.jpg|thumb|Governor Salman bin Abdulaziz with [[Vladimir Putin]] in 2007]] Salman was appointed deputy governor of [[Riyadh Province]] in 17 March 1954, aged 19, and held the post until 19 April 1955.<ref name=\"Aawsat\">{{cite web|title=Profile: New Saudi Defense Minister Prince Salman bin Abdulaziz |url=http://www.aawsat.net/2011/11/article55244468 |work=Asharq Al-Awsat |accessdate=14 February 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150214200738/http://www.aawsat.net/2011/11/article55244468 |archivedate=14 February 2015 |df= }}</ref> He was appointed the provincial governor in 5 February 1963,<ref name=moi/> and remained in that office until 5 November 2011.<ref name=sew1/>\n\nAs governor, he contributed to the development of [[Riyadh]] from a mid-sized town into a major urban metropolis. He served as an important liaison to attract tourism, capital projects and foreign investment to his country. He favored political and economic relationships with the West.<ref name=pbs/> During his governorship, Salman recruited advisors from [[King Saud University]].<ref>Joseph A. Kechichian. Succession in Saudi Arabia. New York: Palgrave, 2001. Print.</ref>\n\nDuring Salman's five decades as Riyadh governor, he became adept at managing the delicate balance of clerical, tribal, and princely interests that determine Saudi policy.<ref>[http://uk.businessinsider.com/heres-everything-we-know-about-the-new-saudi-king-2015-1?r=US Here's Everything We Know About The New Saudi King] Business Insider. 23 January 2015. Retrieved 27 January 2015.</ref> He was also the chairman of the King Abdulaziz Foundation for Research and Archives (KAFRA),<ref>{{cite news|last=M. Taha|first=Sharif|title=Sharjah ruler among 18 to be honored by Prince Salyman|url=http://arabnews.com/saudiarabia/article626065.ece|accessdate=12 May 2012|newspaper=Arab News|date=5 May 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120509193610/http://arabnews.com/saudiarabia/article626065.ece|archivedate=9 May 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> King Abdulaziz Museum,<ref name=anews08>{{cite news|title=In-Depth Study of King Faisal's Life Urged |url=http://archive.arabnews.com/?page=1&section=0&article=109790&d=11&m=5&y=2008 |accessdate=8 June 2012 |newspaper=Arab News |date=11 May 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120616061137/http://archive.arabnews.com/?page=1 |archivedate=16 June 2012 |df= }}</ref> the [[Prince Salman Center for Disability Research]] and the Prince Fahd bin Salman Charitable Society for the Care of Kidney Patients.<ref name=\"Aawsat\"/>\n\nKing Salman also undertook several foreign tours while he was governor. In 1974, he visited [[Kuwait]], [[Bahrain]] and [[Qatar]] to strengthen Saudi Arabia's relationship with those nations. During his visit to [[Montreal]], Canada in 1991, he inaugurated a gallery. In 1996, he was received in the [[\u00c9lys\u00e9e Palace]] in [[Paris]] by the then-French president [[Jacques Chirac]]. The same year he toured [[Bosnia and Herzegovina]] to give donations to the Muslim citizens of the country. Being a part of an Asian tour in 1998, Salman visited [[Pakistan]], [[Japan]], [[Brunei]]<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Cafiero|first=Giorgio|last2=Karasik|first2=Theodore|year=2017|title=King Salman's Return to Brunei Two Decades Later|url=http://nbn-resolving.de/urn:nbn:de:0168-ssoar-50995-9|journal=IndraStra Global|issue=3|page=5}}</ref> and [[China]].<ref>{{cite web|title=\u0627\u0644\u062c\u0648\u0644\u0627\u062a \u0627\u0644\u062e\u0627\u0631\u062c\u064a\u0629 \u0644\u0633\u0644\u0645\u0627\u0646.. \u062f\u0639\u0645 \u0644\u0644\u0639\u0644\u0627\u0642\u0627\u062a \u0648\u062a\u0639\u0632\u064a\u0632 \u0644\u0644\u0631\u0624\u064a\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0633\u0639\u0648\u062f\u064a\u0629|url=http://www.al-madina.com/node/386509|work=Al Madina|accessdate=14 February 2015}}</ref>\n\nAccording to the ''Washington Post'', Saudi journalist the late [[Jamal Khashoggi]] \"criticized Prince Salman, then governor of Riyadh and head of the Saudi committee for support to the [[mujahideen|Afghan mujahideen]], for unwisely funding [[Salafism|Salafist]] extremist groups that were undermining the war [in Afghanistan against the Soviets].\"<ref name=\"ignatius\">{{cite news |title=Jamal Khashoggi's long road to the doors of the Saudi Consulate |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/global-opinions/jamal-khashoggis-long-road-to-the-doors-of-the-saudi-consulate/2018/10/12/b461d6f4-ce1a-11e8-920f-dd52e1ae4570_story.html?noredirect=on |work=The Washington Post |date=12 October 2018}}</ref>\n\nUnder Salman, Riyadh became one of the richest cities in the Middle East and an important place for trade and commerce. There were also infrastructural advances including schools, universities and sports stadiums.<ref name=\"Aawsat\"/> About the province, he said:\n\n<blockquote>Every village or town in the Riyadh Region is dear to me, and holds a special place in my heart&nbsp;... I witnessed every step taken by the city of Riyadh, and for this reason it is difficult for me to think about being far away from Riyadh.<ref name=\"Aawsat\"/> </blockquote>\n\n==Second in line==\n[[File:Leon Panetta with Prince Salman bin Abd al-Aziz Al Saud at the Pentagon April 2012.jpg|thumb|US Secretary of Defense [[Leon Panetta]] with Salman at the [[The Pentagon|Pentagon]] in April 2012]]\nOn 5 November 2011, Salman was appointed Second Deputy Prime Minister and [[Armed Forces of Saudi Arabia|Minister of Defense]], replacing his full brother, the late [[Sultan bin Abdulaziz|Crown Prince Sultan]] (at Defense).<ref name=\"bbcn2011\">{{cite news|title=Saudi Arabia names Prince Salman as new defence minister|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-middle-east-15607814|accessdate=26 May 2012|publisher=BBC News|date=5 November 2011}}</ref> [[Sattam bin Abdul Aziz|Prince Sattam bin Abdulaziz]] was named governor of Riyadh Province. Prince Salman was also named a member of the [[National Security Council (Saudi Arabia)|National Security Council (NSC)]] on the same day.<ref name=\"aps27oct\">{{cite news|title=The Allegiance Council|url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/The+Allegiance+Council.-a0272373988|accessdate=16 March 2013|work=APS Diplomat News Service|date=27 October 2011}}</ref>\n\nIt is speculated that he was placed in the immediate line of succession due to his personal qualities. First, he has a conciliatory and diplomatic nature. He headed the family council, called The Descendants' Council (''Majlis al Uthra'' in Arabic), that was established by King Fahd in 2000 to solve family matters, reach consensus and try to avoid any publicly embarrassing behaviour by some family members.<ref name=tk2712>{{cite web|last=Kapoor|first=Talal|title=Nayif's Passing \u2013 The Family Regroups|url=http://www.datarabia.com/royals/viewCommentary.do?id=88025|work=Datarabia|accessdate=7 July 2012|date=2 July 2012}}</ref><ref name=ata>{{cite journal|author=Amir Taheri|title=Saudi Arabia: Change Begins within the Family|journal=The Journal of the National Committee on American Foreign Policy|year=2012|volume=34|issue=3|pages=138\u2013143|doi=10.1080/10803920.2012.686725}}</ref> Second, Salman belongs to the \"middle generation\" in the royal family; therefore, he could develop close ties with both generations socially and culturally. Last, as a result of his long-term governorship, he had developed a network of relationships within Arab and international circles.<ref name=\"alakhbar\" />\n\nSalman continued the policy of [[Saudi-led intervention in Bahrain|military intervention in Bahrain]], to try to crush the [[Bahrain uprising]]. In April 2012, Salman visited both the United States and the United Kingdom where he met with US President [[Barack Obama]] and British Prime Minister [[David Cameron]].<ref name=tarabia12>{{cite news|title=Saudi Prince dead, Salman likely successor|url=http://www.tradearabia.com/news/LAW_219067.html|accessdate=17 June 2012|work=Trade Arabia|date=16 June 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"gsn21jun12\">{{cite journal|title=Al Saud move with speed to reconfigure top team after Nayef's death|journal=Gulf States Newsletter|date=21 June 2012|volume=36|issue=926|url=http://www.gsn-online.com/sites/default/files/GSN%20926.pdf|accessdate=23 February 2013}}</ref> 2013 saw Saudi military spending climb to $67bn, overtaking that of the UK, France and Japan to place fourth globally.<ref>\"Saudis lead Middle East military spending\". 14 April 2014. Al Jazeera. Retrieved 14 April 2014.</ref> As defense minister, Salman was head of the military as Saudi Arabia joined the United States and other Arab countries in carrying out airstrikes against the Islamic State in Iraq and Syria in 2014.\n\n==Crown Prince==\n[[File:Secretary of Defense Chuck Hagel meets with Crown Prince and Minister of Defense Salman bin Abdulaziz al Saud in Riyadh, Saudi Arabia, April 23, 2013 (Pic 2).jpg|thumb|Crown Prince Salman meeting US Secretary of Defense [[Chuck Hagel]], 23 April 2013]]\nOn 18 June 2012, Salman was appointed as [[Crown Prince of Saudi Arabia]] shortly after the death of his brother, Crown Prince [[Nayef bin Abdul-Aziz Al Saud]].<ref name=bbcnom>{{cite news|last=Patrick|first=Neil|title=Saudi Arabia: Crown Prince's death raises succession questions|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-middle-east-18494785|accessdate=17 June 2012|publisher=BBC|date=17 June 2012}}</ref><ref name=dav19june>{{cite journal|last=Roberts|first=David|title=Saudi Succession after the Death of Crown Prince Nayef|journal=RUSI Analysis|date=19 June 2012|url=http://www.rusi.org/go.php?structureID=commentary&ref=C4FE08BAF7F8BE|accessdate=12 April 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130605181424/http://www.rusi.org/go.php?structureID=commentary&ref=C4FE08BAF7F8BE|archivedate=5 June 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Prince Salman was also made First Deputy Prime minister.<ref name=reu1812/> His nomination as crown prince and deputy prime minister was seen by some as a signal that [[Abdullah of Saudi Arabia|King Abdullah]]'s cautious reforms were likely to continue.<ref name=reu1812>{{cite news|author-link=Angus McDowall|last=McDowall|first=Angus|title=Saudi appoints Prince Salman as crown prince|url=http://uk.reuters.com/article/2012/06/18/uk-saudi-crownprince-appointment-idUKBRE85H15K20120618|accessdate=18 June 2012|agency=Reuters|date=18 June 2012}}</ref> On the other hand, Saudi reformists stated that while Prince Salman, in contrast to other Saudi royals, took a more diplomatic approach towards them, he could not be considered a political reformer.<ref name=ft1226>{{cite news|last=Allam|first=Abeer|title=Saudi Arabia: In a restless realm|url=http://www.ft.com/intl/cms/s/0/59c7492e-e07b-11e1-9335-00144feab49a.html|accessdate=26 August 2012|newspaper=Financial Times|date=26 August 2012}}</ref> They also argued that, like King Abdullah, Salman focused mainly on economic improvement rather than political change.<ref name=ft1226/>\n\nOn 27 August 2012, the Royal Court announced that Salman was in charge of state affairs whilst King Abdullah was out of the country.<ref name=reuriaydh>{{cite news|title=Crown prince in charge as Saudi king leaves on holiday|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2012/08/27/us-saudi-king-travel-idUSBRE87Q0H120120827|accessdate=27 August 2012|agency=Reuters|date=27 August 2012|location=Riyadh}}</ref> Prince Salman launched a [[Twitter]] account on 23 February 2013.<ref name=aa26feb>{{cite news|title=Saudi Crown Prince Salman launches Twitter account|url=http://english.alarabiya.net/articles/2013/02/26/268493.html|accessdate=3 March 2013|publisher=Al Arabiya|date=26 February 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130226205133/http://english.alarabiya.net/articles/2013/02/26/268493.html|archive-date=26 February 2013|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>  In September 2012, Salman was named as the deputy chairman of the military service council.<ref>{{cite news|title=Saudi- Authority to monitor audiovisual media |url=http://www.menafn.com/menafn/1093553820/Saudi-Authority-to-monitor-audiovisual-media |accessdate=4 September 2012 |work=MEFAFN |date=4 September 2012 |agency=Arab News |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140814005012/http://www.menafn.com/menafn/1093553820/Saudi-Authority-to-monitor-audiovisual-media |archivedate=14 August 2014 |df= }}</ref> He is a strong advocate for [[philanthropy]] in poor Muslim nations such as [[Somalia]], [[Sudan]], [[Bangladesh]] and [[Afghanistan]].<ref name=pbs/>\n\n==King of Saudi Arabia==\n[[File:King Salman bin Abdulaziz of Saudi Arabia bids farewell to President Barack Obama at Erga Palace in Riyadh, Saudi Arabia.jpg|thumb|left|US President [[Barack Obama]] shakes hands with King Salman, Riyadh, 27 January 2015]]\n\nOn 23 January 2015, Salman, aged 79, inherited the throne after his half-brother Abdullah died of [[pneumonia]] at the age of 90. The new king issued a statement which read \"His Highness Salman bin Abdulaziz Al Saud and all members of the family and the nation mourn [[Custodian of the Two Holy Mosques]] King Abdullah bin Abdulaziz, who passed away at exactly 1 am this morning.\" He appointed his younger half-brother [[Muqrin of Saudi Arabia|Prince Muqrin]] as the [[Crown Prince of Saudi Arabia|Crown Prince]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Saudi Arabia buries its king: Thousands gather in Mecca as King Abdullah is laid to rest in Riyadh after losing battle with pneumonia|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-2922592/Has-Saudi-Arabia-s-King-Abdullah-died-battle-pneumonia.html#v-4006896776001|work=Daily Mail|accessdate=17 February 2015}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Secretary Kerry Walks With Saudi King Salman After He Arrived At Andrews Air Force Base Before Meeting With President Obama (21098397176).jpg|thumb|US Secretary of State [[John Kerry]] with Salman at [[Andrews Field|Andrews Air Force Base]] in Camp Springs, Maryland, 3 September 2015]]\n[[File:Jokowi Salman 2017 crop.jpg|thumb|King Salman and Indonesian President [[Joko Widodo]] in [[Jakarta]], 1 March 2017]]\nAfter coming to power, Salman reshuffled the cabinet on 30 January 2015. Khalid bin Ali bin Abdullah al-Humaidan was made the [[Al Mukhabarat Al A'amah|intelligence chief]]. [[Prince Bandar bin Sultan]] was removed from his post in the [[Saudi National Security Council|security council]] and the adviser to the monarch was also removed as were the former monarch's sons [[Turki bin Abdullah Al Saud|Turki]] as governor of [[Riyadh]] and [[Mishaal bin Abdullah Al Saud|Mishaal]] as governor of [[Mecca]]. [[Ali al-Naimi]] remained the minister of [[Ministry of Petroleum and Mineral Resources of Saudi Arabia|petroleum and mineral resources]], as did [[Saud al-Faisal]] of the [[Ministry of Foreign Affairs]] and [[Ibrahim Abdulaziz Al-Assaf|Ibrahim Al-Assaf]] as [[Ministry of Finance (Saudi Arabia)|finance minister]]. Salman also \"gave a bonus of two months' salary to all Saudi state employees and military personnel\", including pensioners and students, while also asking citizens to \"not forget me in your prayers\".<ref>{{cite web|title=Saudi Arabia's King Salman unveils cabinet reshuffle|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-31052071|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=3 February 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2015, he received [[Prince Charles]] during his six-day tour in the Middle East. They \"exchanged cordial talks and reviewed bilateral relations\" between the countries.<ref>{{cite web|title=King Salman receives Prince Charles in Riyadh|url=http://english.alarabiya.net/en/News/middle-east/2015/02/10/Saudi-King-Salman-receives-Prince-Charles-in-Riyadh-.html|publisher=Al Arabiya|accessdate=14 February 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Early reforms===\nOne of the first things the King and his son, [[Mohammad bin Salman]], did was to streamline the government bureaucracy. On the death of King Abdullah, there were as many as eleven government secretariats, and all of these were abolished and reconstituted as only two, the [[Council of Political and Security Affairs (Saudi Arabia)|Council of Political and Security Affairs]] (CPSA), headed by Deputy Crown prince [[Mohammed bin Nayef]], and the [[Council of Economic and Development Affairs (Saudi Arabia)|Council for Economic and Development Affairs]] (CEDA), headed by the Secretary-General of the Royal Court, Prince Mohammad bin Salman, who were given free rein to completely reorganize the government<ref>[http://gulfnews.com/news/gulf/saudi-arabia/mohammad-bin-nayef-takes-leading-role-in-saudi-arabia-1.1458374 Mohammad bin Nayef takes leading role in Saudi Arabia] ''Gulf News''. 17 February 2015. Retrieved 13 March 2015.</ref> and cementing the power of the Sudairi faction, to which both princes belong.\n\n===Yemen military intervention===\n{{main|Saudi Arabian-led intervention in Yemen}}\nIn March 2015, the king ordered the bombing of Yemen and [[Saudi Arabian-led intervention in Yemen|military intervention]] against the [[Shia Islam|Shia]] [[Houthis]] and forces loyal to former President [[Ali Abdullah Saleh]], who was deposed in the 2011 uprising.<ref>\"[http://edition.cnn.com/2015/03/26/middleeast/yemen-saudi-arabia-airstrikes/ Saudi-led coalition strikes rebels in Yemen, inflaming tensions in region]\". [[CNN]]. 27 March 2015.</ref> He first put together a coalition of ten [[Sunni Islam|Sunni Muslim]] countries. Code-named Operation Decisive Storm, this was the first time the [[Royal Saudi Air Force|Saudi Air Force]] had launched airstrikes against another country since the 1990\u201391 Gulf War.\n\nAccording to [[Farea Al-Muslim]], direct [[war crimes]] have been committed during the conflict; for example, an [[Internally displaced person|IDP]] camp was hit by a Saudi airstrike.<ref>{{cite web|last=Kasinof|first=Laura|title=How Yemen's Civil Conflict Turned Into a Regional Proxy War |url=http://www.thenation.com/article/206161/how-yemens-civil-conflict-turned-regional-proxy-war|work=[[The Nation]]}}</ref> [[Human Rights Watch]] (HRW) wrote that the Saudi-led air campaign had conducted airstrikes in apparent violation of the [[Law of war|laws of war]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Yemen: Saudi-Led Airstrikes Used Cluster Munitions |url=https://www.hrw.org/news/2015/05/03/yemen-saudi-led-airstrikes-used-cluster-munitions |publisher=Human Rights Watch |date=3 May 2015 }}</ref> Human rights groups have also criticized Saudi Arabia for the alleged use of cluster bombs against Yemeni civilians.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Fanack|title=A New Wind in Saudi Arabia|url=https://chronicle.fanack.com/saudi-arabia/history-past-to-present/a-new-wind-in-saudi-arabia/|website=Fanack.com|accessdate=14 July 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Crown Prince changes===\n{{multiple image|total_width=300\n|image1=Prince Mohammed bin Naif bin Abdulaziz 2013-01-16 (2).jpg\n|image2=Crown Prince Mohammad bin Salman Al Saud - 2017.jpg\n|footer= [[Muhammad bin Nayef]] in January 2013 (left); [[Mohammed bin Salman]] in May 2017\n}}\nIn April 2015, three months after becoming king, Salman appointed a full nephew, [[Muhammad bin Nayef]], as the new Crown Prince to replace his youngest brother [[Muqrin bin Abdulaziz|Prince Muqrin]]. Furthermore, he made his son, Mohammad bin Salman, the Deputy Crown Prince. Almost all powers under the king were concentrated in the hands of the crown prince and deputy crown prince, both of whom held the portfolio determining all security and economic development issues in Saudi Arabia.<ref name=\"Saudi king resets succession to cope with turbulent times\">{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-saudi-politics-idUSKBN0NK05W20150429 |title=Saudi king resets succession to cope with turbulent times |last=McDowall |first=Angus |last2=Aboudi |first2=Sami |date=29 April 2015 |editor-last=Maclean |editor-first=William |editor2-last=Fletcher |editor2-first=Philippa |editor3-last=Graff |editor3-first=Peter |agency=[[Reuters]]   |location=Riyadh |archive-url=https://archive.is/20170514195316/http://www.reuters.com/article/us-saudi-politics-idUSKBN0NK05W20150429 |archive-date=14 May 2017 |url-status=live |access-date=23 April 2016 |last3=Hashem |first3=Mostafa |last4=El Dahan |first4=Maha |last5=Shamseddine |first5=Reem |last6=Gloystein |first6=Henning |last7=Mohammed |first7=Arshad |df= }}</ref>\n\nKing Salman then removed Muhammad bin Nayef from the line of succession to the Saudi throne on 21 June 2017 and designated his son Mohammad bin Salman as the new crown prince.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aljazeera.com/news/2017/06/saudi-arabia-appoints-king-salman-son-crown-prince-170621033707437.html|title=Mohammed bin Salman named Saudi Arabia's crown prince|publisher=Al Jazeera|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170621091448/http://www.aljazeera.com/news/2017/06/saudi-arabia-appoints-king-salman-son-crown-prince-170621033707437.html|archivedate=21 June 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref> At the same time, King Salman removed Muhammad bin Nayef from his other positions in the Saudi government.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cnn.com/2017/06/21/middleeast/saudi-arabia-crown-prince/index.html|title=Saudi Arabia's king replaces nephew with son as heir to throne|author=Nicole Chavez, Tamara Qiblawi and James Griffiths|website=CNN}}</ref> Mohammad bin Salman has been described as the [[power behind the throne]].<ref>[http://www.economist.com/saudi_interview?fsrc=scn%2Ftw_ec%2Ftranscript_interview_with_muhammad_bin_salman Transcript: Interview with Muhammad bin Salman] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160109180902/http://www.economist.com/saudi_interview?fsrc=scn%2Ftw_ec%2Ftranscript_interview_with_muhammad_bin_salman|date=9 January 2016}} ''The Economist'', 6 January 2016.</ref>\n\n===KSRelief===\nIn May 2015 the King Salman Center for Relief and Humanitarian Aid (KSRelief) was established to deliver aid internationally to victims of civil war and natural disaster, working with the UN and other agencies. As of June 2018, KSRelief has implemented more than 400 individual projects in 40 countries at a cost of $1.8 billion.<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=King Salman relief center implements 428 projects worth $1.7 bln |url=https://english.alarabiya.net/en/News/gulf/2018/06/26/King-Salman-relief-center-implements-428-projects-worth-1-7-bln.html |work=[[Al Arabiya]] |location= |date=26 June 2018 |access-date=24 September 2018}}</ref> Moreover, in 2018, KSRelief assisted 180,555 Syrian patients living in [[Zaatari refugee camp|Zataari]] Syrian refugees camp in [[Jordan]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.arabnews.com/node/1430111/saudi-arabia|title=King Salman Humanitarian aid agency treats 180,000 Syrian patients in Jordan|date=2019-01-04|website=Arab News|language=en|access-date=2019-01-04}}</ref> In 2019, KSRelief signed a memorandum of cooperation with [[UNICEF]] that aims at enhancing cooperation in the humanitarian field, exchanging knowledge, sharing experiences, promoting voluntary work and boosting capacity building programs.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.arabnews.com/node/1451876/saudi-arabia|title=KSRelief inks cooperation deal with UNICEF|date=2019-02-13|website=Arab News|language=en|access-date=2019-02-18}}</ref> Until 2019, the center provided 1,839 Yemeni civilians wounded during the war with prosthetic limbs for a total amount of $2.3 million.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.arabnews.com/node/1457451/saudi-arabia|title=Saudi Arabia's relief center prosthetic limbs project benefits 1,839 Yemenis|date=2019-02-24|website=Arab News|language=en|access-date=2019-02-25}}</ref>\n\nIn its ongoing efforts to support people of Yemen, KSRelief organized a vocational training program to train women in [[Yemen]] to enable them to earn money for themselves and their families.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.arabnews.com/node/1462856/saudi-arabia|title=KSRelief launches pilot project for female breadwinners in Yemen|date=2019-03-07|website=Arab News|language=en|access-date=2019-03-07}}</ref> In a similar context, under the umbrella of the UN, KSRelief has led an international team to implement a rehabilitation project for the children affected by war in Yemen.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.arabnews.com/node/1462721/saudi-arabia|title=Saudi Arabia's aid agency takes steps to improve rehab projects|date=2019-03-06|website=Arab News|language=en|access-date=2019-03-07}}</ref> Moreover, as part of the 40th session of the UN Human Rights' Council, KSRelief organized an event entitled: Children and the Humanitarian Crisis in Yemen where it presented a number of facts and figures related to the amount of assistance provided by the center to the people of Yemen. This includes the implementation of 328 projects for an amount of $2 billion.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.spa.gov.sa/viewfullstory.php?lang=en&newsid=1896914#1896914|title=KSrelief Holds Seminar on Children, Humanitarian Crisis, in Yemen, in Geneva The official Saudi Press Agency|website=www.spa.gov.sa|access-date=2019-03-13}}</ref> Furthermore, in 2018 alone KSRelief provided medical services to 2,501,897 Yemenis.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.arabnews.com/node/1478721/saudi-arabia|title=Saudi Arabia's KSRelief team discusses Yemen livelihood project|date=2019-04-07|website=Arab News|language=en|access-date=2019-04-07}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, KSrelief signed a number of agreements with different civil society organizations to implement relief projects for the benefit of Palestinian and Syrian refugees as well as the host Lebanese community. An agreement was concluded with the UNHCR to support the families affected by war for an amount of $5 million. Another one was concluded with IOM to help Syrian refugees under the poverty line for an amount of $3.8 million.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.arabnews.com/node/1487791/saudi-arabia|title=KSRelief signs agreements for relief to Lebanese, Syrians and Palestinians|date=2019-04-25|website=Arab News|language=en|access-date=2019-05-01}}</ref>\n\n=== Human rights ===\nIn February 2012, [[Ali Mohammed Baqir al-Nimr]] was arrested for participating in, and encouraging, pro-[[democracy]] protests, when he was 16 or 17 years old. In May 2014, Ali Al-Nimr was sentenced to be executed, despite the minimum age for execution being 18 when a crime is committed.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://usuncut.com/world/ali-mohammed-al-nimr-father-speaks-out/|title=Father of Ali, Saudi teen slated for public execution, speaks out}}</ref> Ali Al-Nimr has reported that he was tortured during his detention. As of 23 September 2015, the sentence awaited ratification by King Salman.<ref>Zafar Gondal, [http://www.esohr.org/en/?page_id=756 \"Analysis of court Judgment and conviction of Ali bin Mohammad bin Baqir Al-Nimr \u2013 Saudi Arabia\"], London, 15 December 2015. Retrieved 20 February 2015</ref>\n\nIn February 2015, a man from [[Hafar Al-Batin]] was sentenced to death for rejecting Islam.<ref>{{cite web | title= Saudi Arabia court gives death penalty to man who renounced his Muslim faith|url= https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/middleeast/saudiarabia/11431509/Saudi-Arabia-court-gives-death-penalty-to-man-who-renounced-his-Muslim-faith.html|work=The Daily Telegraph|date=24 February 2015 }}</ref> In June 2015, Saudi Arabia's Supreme Court upheld the sentence of 1,000 lashes and 10 years in prison for [[Raif Badawi]], a Saudi Arabian blogger who was imprisoned in 2012 after being charged for 'insulting Islam'.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-33039815|title=Saudi court upholds blogger's 10 years and 1,000 lashes|publisher=BBC|date=7 June 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Iran and Syria===\n[[File:Donald Trump and King Salman bin Abdulaziz Al Saud talk together, May 2017.jpg|thumb|US President [[Donald Trump]] with King Salman, Riyadh, 20 May 2017]]\nUS Defense Secretary [[Ashton Carter]] met with the King and his Arabian military counterpart, Deputy Crown Prince [[Mohammad bin Salman]], at Jeddah to answer regional security concerns in the Kingdom and the Gulf states over lifting Iranian economic and conventional military sanctions as the [[Joint Comprehensive Plan of Action]] outlines. The King has misgivings over the deal since it would increase the regional power of Iran especially in the proxy conflicts in Syria, Yemen, and elsewhere.<ref>Tait, Robert and Foster, Peter. (22 July 2015) \"Saudi Arabia's King Salman backs Israel over Iran nuclear deal concerns\". The Telegraph. Retrieved 22 July 2015. [https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/middleeast/saudiarabia/11756739/Saudi-Arabias-King-Salman-backs-Israel-over-Iran-nuclear-deal-concerns.html The Telegraph website]</ref> In January 2016, Saudi Arabia executed the prominent [[Shia Islam in Saudi Arabia|Saudi Shia]] cleric [[Nimr al-Nimr|Sheikh Nimr]].<ref name=\"nimr\">{{cite web | title=Saudi execution of Shia cleric sparks outrage in Middle East |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2016/jan/02/saudi-execution-of-shia-cleric-sparks-outrage-in-middle-east |work=[[The Guardian]]| date=2 January 2016}}</ref> Iran warned that the [[House of Saud]] would pay a high price for the execution of Sheikh Nimr by God's will.<ref name=\"nimr\"/>\n\nSaudi Arabia has emerged as the main group to finance and arm the rebels fighting against the [[Syria]]n government.<ref>\"[https://www.reuters.com/article/2013/05/31/us-syria-crisis-saudi-insight-idUSBRE94U0ZV20130531 Saudi edges Qatar to control Syrian rebel support]\". Reuters. 31 May 2013</ref> Saudi Arabia openly backed the [[Army of Conquest]], an umbrella rebel group that reportedly included an [[al-Qaeda]] linked [[al-Nusra Front]] and another [[Salafi jihadism|Salafi]] coalition known as [[Ahrar al-Sham]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/middle-east/syria-crisis-turkey-and-saudi-arabia-shock-western-countries-by-supporting-antiassad-jihadists-10242747.html |title=Turkey and Saudi Arabia alarm the West by backing Islamist extremists the Americans had bombed in Syria  |author=Kim Sengupta |newspaper=The Independent |date=12 May 2015}}</ref><ref>\"[http://weekly.ahram.org.eg/News/12392.aspx Gulf allies and \u2018Army of Conquest\u2019]\". ''[[Al-Ahram Weekly]]''. 28 May 2015.</ref><ref>\"[https://news.yahoo.com/army-conquest-rebel-alliance-pressures-syria-regime-090529121.html 'Army of Conquest' rebel alliance pressures Syria regime]\". Yahoo News. 28 April 2015.</ref>\n\nIn May 2019, leaders of Gulf and Arab states held two emergency summits in Mecca to present a united front to Iran.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/jun/01/saudi-king-warns-attacks-on-oil-stations-threaten-global-supply-iran Saudi king warns attacks on oil stations threaten global supply]. ''The Guardian''. 31 May 2019.</ref> Salman accused Iran of threatening global oil supplies and shipping at a meeting of Arab leaders that called on the international community to confront Tehran following attacks on shipping and rising tensions in the oil rich region.<ref>[https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2019-05-30/saudi-king-accuses-iran-of-threatening-global-maritime-traffic Saudi King Accuses Iran of Threatening Global Oil Supplies]. ''Bloomberg''. 30 May 2019.</ref> Salman said \"what the Iranian regime is doing, from intervening in regional countries\u2019 affairs and developing its nuclear program, threatening global maritime traffic and global oil supplies, is a blatant violation of the treaties and principles of the United Nations.\" He urged the international community should \"use all means to deter this regime.\"<ref>[https://www.dw.com/en/saudi-king-iran-backed-groups-threaten-global-oil-supplies/a-48997918 Saudi king: Iran-backed groups threaten global oil supplies]. ''DW''. 1 June 2019.</ref>\n\n===Panama Papers revelations===\nKing Salman has been implicated in the [[Panama Papers]] leaks, with two companies originating in the [[British Virgin Islands]] taking mortgages in excess of US$34 million to purchase property in [[central London]]. His role has not been specified.<ref name=\"telesur\">{{cite news |title=Saudi King, UAE President at the Center of the Panama Papers |url=http://www.telesurtv.net/english/news/Saudi-King-UAE-President-at-the-Center-of-the-Panama-Papers-20160404-0024.html |newspaper=[[TeleSUR]] |date=4 April 2016 }}</ref><ref>\"[http://www.middleeasteye.net/news/complete-guide-secret-dealings-middle-east-leaders-revealed-panama-papers-leak-662088930 The who's who of Middle East leaders and their secret billions]\". Middle East Eye. 4 April 2016.</ref> According to [[TeleSUR]], \"King Salman\u2019s net worth is estimated at US$17.0 billion.\"<ref name=\"telesur\"/> The then-Crown Prince Muhammad bin Nayef has also been [[List of people named in the Panama Papers|named]] in association with the Papers.<ref>\"[http://www.france24.com/en/20160404-panama-papers-politicians-named-europe-africa A world tour of the politicians named in the Panama Papers]\". [[France 24]]. 5 April 2016.</ref>\n\n===Later reforms===\nFurther government reforms took place in June 2018, when King Salman replaced the labor and Islamic affairs ministers.<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=King Salman's reign sees largest structural reforms in history of Saudi Arabia |url=https://english.alarabiya.net/en/features/2018/06/02/King-Salman-s-reign-sees-largest-structural-reforms-in-history-of-Saudi-Arabia.html |work=[[Al Arabiya]] |location= |date=2 June 2018 |access-date=24 September 2018}}</ref> The appointment as labor minister of Ahmed al-Rajhi, a businessman, signalled a growing role for private sector expertise in the Saudi government.<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=FaceOf: Ahmed bin Suleiman Al-Rajhi, new minister of labor and social development|url=http://www.arabnews.com/node/1314961/saudi-arabia |work=[[Arab News]] |location= |date=4 June 2018 |access-date=24 September 2018}}</ref> The new minister for Islamic affairs, Abdullatif al-Alsheikh, had previously been credited with reining in the power of the religious police.<ref name=FT070218>{{cite news |last=Al Omran |first=Ahmed |date=2 June 2018 |title=Saudi Arabia creates new departments in reshuffle |url=https://www.ft.com/content/1459999c-668e-11e8-b6eb-4acfcfb08c11 |work=[[Financial Times]] |location= |access-date=24 September 2018}}</ref>\n\nAt the same time King Salman ordered the establishment of a new Ministry of Culture, with responsibility for delivering Saudi Vision 2030's cultural goals; and the Council of Royal Reserves, tasked with environmental protection.<ref name=FT070218/><ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Saudi Arabia seeks ecotourism boost by protecting environment, wildlife |url=http://www.arabnews.com/node/1314391/saudi-arabia |work=[[Arab News]] |location= |date=3 June 2018 |access-date=24 September 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Influence==\n[[File:Abdel Fattah el-Sisi, King Salman of Saudi Arabia, Melania Trump, and Donald Trump, May 2017.jpg|thumb|left|Salman, US President Donald Trump, and Egyptian President [[Abdel Fattah el-Sisi]] touching a glowing orb at the [[2017 Riyadh summit]].]] \nSalman was often a mediator in settling royal conflicts among the extended Al Saud family \u2013 estimated at 4,000 princes. He was a prominent figure of the royal council, which allowed him to select which princes will be delegated which responsibilities of the Kingdom.<ref name=pbs>{{cite web|title=Prince Salman bin Abdulaziz|url=https://www.pbs.org/wnet/wideangle/episodes/the-saudi-question/whos-who-the-house-of-saud/prince-sulayman-ibn-abdul-aziz/2871/|work=PBS|accessdate=26 May 2012}}</ref>\n\nSalman and his family own a media group, including pan-Arab daily ''[[Asharq Al-Awsat]]'' and ''[[Al Eqtisadiah]]''.<ref name=wikileaks2009>{{cite web|title=Ideological and Ownership Trends in the Saudi Media|url=http://www.cablegatesearch.net/cable.php?id=09RIYADH651|work=Wikileaks|accessdate=26 May 2012|date=11 May 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130116083750/http://www.cablegatesearch.net/cable.php?id=09RIYADH651|archivedate=16 January 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=alif>{{cite web|title=9 Challenges Facing The New Crown Prince of Saudi Arabia |url=http://alifarabia.com/2011/10/30/8-challenges-facing-the-new-crown-prince-of-saudi-arabia/ |work=Alifarabia |accessdate=26 May 2012 |date=30 October 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111122012155/http://alifarabia.com/2011/10/30/8-challenges-facing-the-new-crown-prince-of-saudi-arabia/ |archivedate=22 November 2011 |df= }}</ref> Though he owns only ten percent of the [[Saudi Research and Marketing Group]] (SRMG), he is often referred by auditors as its owner.<ref name=wikileaks2009/> He reportedly controls the organization through his son [[Faisal bin Salman bin Abdulaziz Al Saud|Prince Faisal]],<ref name=wikileaks2009/> who is a former chairman of the concern.  The SRMG publishes such daily papers as ''[[Arab News]]'', ''[[Asharq Al-Awsat]]'' and ''[[Al Eqtisadiah]]'' through its subsidiary Saudi Research and Publishing Company (SRPC).<ref>{{cite web|title=Al-Faiz new editor in chief of Arab News|url=http://www.srpc.com/en/node/44|work=SRPC|accessdate=30 April 2012}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Vladimir Putin and Salman of Saudi Arabia (2017-10-05) 1.jpg|thumb|King Salman with Russian President Vladimir Putin, [[Moscow]], 5 October 2017]]\nIn a similar vein, Salman is reported to have some strong alliances with significant journalists. He is said to be close to [[Al Arabiya]] TV director and ''[[Asharq Al-Awsat]]'' journalist Abdelrahman Al Rashid and to [[Othman Al Omeir]], who launched and is the owner of the liberal e-newspaper ''[[Elaph]]''. King Salman is thought to have connections with the ''Elaph'' website.<ref>{{cite web|title=Saudi succession issues|url=http://www.gsn-online.com/SSIs/SAMPLES/documents/GSN845.pdf|work=GSN (Gulf States Newsletter)|accessdate=13 April 2012|date=16 January 2009}}{{dead link|date=January 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n==Views==\nSalman holds traditional views with regards to political reforms and social change.<ref>{{cite web|title=Before he was king, Salman was the family disciplinarian who put princes behind bars|last=Sullivan|first=Kevin|date=23 January 2015|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/salman-is-known-for-mediating-saudi-royal-disputes/2015/01/22/1bc8dc1a-a2b0-11e4-b146-577832eafcb4_story.html|work=[[The Washington Post]]|accessdate= 25 January 2015}}</ref> In November 2002, in reference to charitable organizations accused of terrorism (e.g. [[al-Haramain Foundation]], [[Saudi High Commission for Relief of Bosnia and Herzegovina]]), he stated that he had personally taken part in the activities of such organizations,<ref name=charbris/> but added \"I know the assistance goes to doing good. But if there are those who change some work of charity into evil activities, then it is not the Kingdom's responsibility, nor its people, which helps its Arab and Muslim brothers around the world.\"<ref name=charbris>{{cite web|last=Brisard |first=Jean Charles |title=Terrorism financing. Roots and trends of Saudi terrorism financing |url=http://apgml.org/frameworks/docs/7/TF-Saudi%20financing%20Nov2002%20-%20UN%20Security%20Council.pdf |work=the Security Council, United Nations |accessdate=15 April 2012 |date=19 December 2002 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120321141344/http://www.apgml.org/frameworks/docs/7/TF-Saudi%20financing%20Nov2002%20-%20UN%20Security%20Council.pdf |archivedate=21 March 2012 |df= }}</ref>\n\n[[Al Jazeera English|Al Jazeera]] referred to Salman's views reported in a 2007 [[Contents of the United States diplomatic cables leak (Saudi Arabia)|US diplomatic cable]].<ref name=aljaz1612>{{cite news|last=Carlstrom|first=Gregg|title=Nayef's conservative policies to outlive him|url=http://www.aljazeera.com/indepth/features/2012/06/2012616185546905427.html|accessdate=17 June 2012|publisher=Al Jazeera|date=16 June 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"07RIYADH651\">{{cite document|last=Gfoeller|first=Michael|title=Ambassador's farewell call on Riyadh Provincial Governor Prince Sulayman|id={{WikiLeaks cable|07RIYADH651}}|work=WikiLeaks|date=1 April 2007|url=http://wikileaks.ch/cable/2007/04/07RIYADH651.html|accessdate=1 January 2015|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6VFK1C3dS|archivedate=1 January 2015|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Salman said that \"the pace and extent of reforms depend on social and cultural factors, ... that for social reasons\u2014not [religious] reasons\u2014reforms cannot be imposed by the [Saudi government] or there will be negative reactions, ... [and] that changes have to be introduced in a sensitive and timely manner.\" According to the cable, he said that \"democracy should not be imposed\" in Saudi Arabia, since the country \"is composed of tribes and regions and if democracy were imposed, each tribe and region would have its political party.\"<ref name=\"07RIYADH651\"/>\n\n==Personal life==\n[[File:Salman bin Abdullaziz Al Saud in his Youth.jpg|thumbnail|left|Salman in his youth]]\n\nSalman bin Abdulaziz has been married three times.<ref name=arabt18jun>{{cite news|title=Prince Sulayman Named Saudi 'Crown Prince'|url=http://www.arabtimesonline.com/NewsDetails/tabid/96/smid/414/ArticleID/184632/reftab/96/Default.aspx|accessdate=26 February 2013|work=Arab Times|date=18 June 2012|location=Riyadh}}</ref> {{As of|2017}}, he had thirteen children.<ref>{{cite web | title = Who is Mohammed bin Salman, the 31-year-old future king of Saudi Arabia? | last = Sanchez | first = Raf  | work = The Telegraph | date = 21 June 2017 | accessdate = 12 January 2018 | url = https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2017/06/21/mohammed-bin-salman-31-year-old-future-king-saudi-arabia/ }}</ref> His first wife was Sultana bint Turki Al Sudairi,<ref name=erguard>{{cite news|title=Princess Sultana|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=-PRVAAAAIBAJ&sjid=M-IDAAAAIBAJ&pg=6528,4734357&dq=king+fahd%27s+wife&hl=en|accessdate=9 February 2013|newspaper=Eugene Register Guard|date=19 June 1983}}</ref> who died aged 71 in late-July 2011.<ref name=saugaz3811/><ref>{{cite news|author=David D. Kirkpatrick|title=Surprising Saudi Rises as a Prince Among Princes|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/06/07/world/middleeast/surprising-saudi-rises-as-a-prince-among-princes.html|accessdate=29 October 2015|work=The New York Times|date=6 June 2015|location=Riyadh}}</ref> She was a first cousin of Salman, being a daughter of his maternal uncle Turki bin Ahmad Al Sudairi,<ref name=saugaz3811>{{cite news|title=Sultana, wife of Riyadh Emir, passes away |url=http://www.saudigazette.com.sa/index.cfm?method=home.regcon&contentID=20110803106640 |accessdate=26 May 2012 |newspaper=Saudi Gazette |date=3 August 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131228132942/http://www.saudigazette.com.sa/index.cfm?method=home.regcon&contentID=20110803106640 |archivedate=28 December 2013 |df= }}</ref> who was a former governor of the [[Asir Province]].<ref name=datsultana>{{cite web|title=Sultana bint Ahmad bin Muhammad al Sudairi|url=http://www.datarabia.com/royals/viewBio.do?id=176248|work=Datarabia|accessdate=8 May 2012}}</ref> Sultana Al Sudairi supported the Prince Fahd bin Salman Charitable Society for the Care of Kidney Patients and other charitable organizations in the country.<ref name=siasat2011/> His children from this marriage are [[Fahd bin Salman bin Abdulaziz Al Saud|Prince Fahd]] (died 2001), [[Sultan bin Salman Al Saud|Prince Sultan]], [[Ahmed bin Salman bin Abdulaziz Al Saud|Prince Ahmed]] (died 2002), [[Abdulaziz bin Salman Al Saud|Prince Abdulaziz]], [[Faisal bin Salman bin Abdulaziz Al Saud|Prince Faisal]] and [[Hassa bint Salman Al Saud|Princess Hassa]].<ref name=siasat2011>{{cite news|title=Kingdom mourns loss of princess|url=http://www.siasat.com/english/news/kingdom-mourns-loss-princess|accessdate=26 May 2012|newspaper=The Siasat Daily|date=3 August 2011}}</ref>\n\nHis eldest son, Fahd bin Salman, died of [[heart failure]] aged 47 in July 2001.<ref name=tt25jul>{{cite news|title=Death of a Generous man|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/horseracing/3009518/Death-of-a-Generous-man.html|accessdate=3 March 2013|newspaper=The Telegraph|date=25 July 2001}}</ref> His third son, Ahmad bin Salman, died after a [[heart attack]] in July 2002 aged 43.<ref name=usatoday>{{cite news|last=Bradley|first=John R.|title=Prince Ahmed's cousin killed on way to funeral|url=https://www.usatoday.com/sports/horses/stories/2002-07-23-sulayman-funeral_x.htm|accessdate=26 May 2012|newspaper=USA Today|date=23 July 2002}}</ref> Sultan bin Salman became the first person of royal blood, the first-ever [[Arab]], and the first [[Muslim]] to fly in outer space when he flew aboard the [[Space Shuttle Discovery]] ([[STS-51-G]]) in June 1985.<ref name=wstar20jun>{{cite news|title=First Arab astronaut makes a royal tour of space|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=0lg_AAAAIBAJ&sjid=AlMMAAAAIBAJ&pg=990,942020&dq=sulayman+bin+abdulaziz&hl=en|accessdate=3 March 2013|newspaper=The Windsor Star|date=20 June 1985|location=New York|pages=B12}}</ref> Sultan bin Salman is currently the chairman of the Saudi Space Commission.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ssc.gov.sa/index-en.html#about|title=Saudi Space Commission|website=ssc.gov.sa|access-date=2020-03-13}}</ref> Prince Sultan bin Salman was formerly the chairman of the [[Saudi Commission for Tourism & Antiquities]] (SCTA), which later was changed to be the ministry of Tourism.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mt.gov.sa/en/AboutSCTA/Pages/President.aspx|title=Curriculum Vitae|website=mt.gov.sa|access-date=2020-03-13}}</ref> Abdulaziz bin Salman has been the deputy minister of oil since 1995, then the minister of Energy since 2019 <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/saudi-arabia-names-new-energy-minister-11567895724|title=Saudi Arabia Names New Energy Minister|last=Faucon|first=Summer Said, Jared Malsin and Benoit|website=WSJ|language=en-US|access-date=2019-11-25}}</ref><ref name=wikileaks2008>{{cite web|title=Saudi oil assistance to Pakistan proceeding slowly|url=http://www.cablegatesearch.net/cable.php?id=08RIYADH1175|work=Wikileaks|accessdate=26 May 2012|date=30 July 2008|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120526092120/http://cablegatesearch.net/cable.php?id=08RIYADH1175|archivedate=26 May 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Faisal bin Salman is the governor of [[Al Madinah Province|Madinah province]].\n\nHis child from his second marriage with Sarah bint Faisal Al Subai'ai (divorced) is [[Saud Bin Salman bin Abdulaziz al Saud|Prince Saud]]. His children from his third marriage with Fahda bint Falah bin Sultan Al Hathleen<ref>{{cite news|author1=Hugh Miles|title=Saudi Arabia: Eight of King Salman's 11 surviving brothers want to oust him|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/middle-east/saudi-arabia-power-struggle-between-king-salman-and-mohammed-bin-salman-could-bring-down-the-a6706801.html|accessdate=22 April 2016|work=Independent|date=23 October 2015}}</ref> are [[Mohammad bin Salman|Prince Mohammed]], [[Turki bin Salman Al Saud|Prince Turki]], [[Khalid bin Salman bin Abdulaziz Al Saud|Prince Khalid]], Prince Nayif, Prince Bandar, and Prince Rakan.<ref>{{cite web|title=Family Tree of Salman bin Abdulaziz bin Abdul Rahman Al Saud|url=http://www.datarabia.com/royals/famtree.do?id=176822|work=Datarabia|accessdate=1 May 2012}}</ref>\n\nPrince Mohammad was his private adviser at the Ministry of Defense and at the Crown Prince Court.<ref>{{cite news|title=Prince Sultan arrives to Bahrain to attend Bahrain Grand Prix|url=http://www.bna.bh/portal/en/news/505092|accessdate=23 April 2012|agency=Bahrain News Agency|date=22 April 2012}}</ref> Mohammad was appointed as the Minister of Defense and head of the royal court upon his father's accession to the throne in January 2015.<ref>{{cite news|title=Saudi Prince Mohammad bin Salman named defense minister|url=http://english.alarabiya.net/en/News/middle-east/2015/01/23/Saudi-Prince-Mohammad-bin-Salman-appointed-defense-minister-head-of-Royal-Court.html|accessdate=23 January 2015|publisher=Al Arabiya|date=23 January 2015}}</ref> Turki bin Salman became the chairman of the [[Saudi Research and Marketing Group]] in February 2013, replacing his elder brother Faisal bin Salman.<ref name=anews13>{{cite news|title=Prince Turki succeeds Prince Faisal as SRMG chairman|url=http://www.arabnews.com/saudi-arabia/prince-turki-succeeds-prince-faisal-srmg-chairman|accessdate=9 February 2013|newspaper=Arab News|date=9 February 2013}}</ref>\n\nSalman was the closest brother to [[Sultan bin Abdulaziz|Crown Prince Sultan]], having remained at his side during his constant illness and recovery in [[New York City|New York]] and [[Morocco]], from 2008-11.<ref name=alakhbar>{{cite news|last=al Baker |first=Basheer |title=Prince Sulayman Seeks Balance in Saudi Transitional Period |url=http://english.al-akhbar.com/content/prince-sulayman-seeks-balance-saudi-transitional-period |accessdate=23 April 2012 |newspaper=Al Akhbar |date=3 November 2011 }}{{dead link|date=April 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Prince Sultan described him as \"the prince of loyalty\" in a letter sent to him.<ref name=letter>{{cite news|title=Late crown prince's letter shows his deep love toward Sulayman|url=http://www.arabnews.com/node/402044|accessdate=29 July 2012|newspaper=Arab News|date=26 December 2011}}</ref> Salman was also [[Fahd of Saudi Arabia|King Fahd]]'s most trusted adviser during his reign.<ref name=iasps>{{cite journal|last=Wihbey|first=Paul Michael|title=Succession in Saudi Arabia: The not so silent struggle|journal=IASPS Research Papers in Strategy|year=1997|issue=4|url=http://www.iasps.org/strategic4/SA.htm|accessdate=14 May 2012}}</ref><ref name=mvio>{{cite journal|last=Viorst|first=Milton|title=The storm and the citadel|journal=Foreign Affairs|date=January\u2013February 1996|volume=75|issue=1|pages=93\u2013107|url=http://www.foreignaffairs.com/articles/51625/milton-viorst/the-storm-and-the-citadel|accessdate=1 June 2012|doi=10.2307/20047470|jstor=20047470}}</ref>\n\nHis legal counsel was William Jeffress, Jr., of US-based firm, [[Baker Botts|Baker Botts LLP]], in a lawsuit filed by families of victims of the [[September 11th terrorist attacks|11 September terrorist attacks]] from 2002-10.<ref>{{cite web|title=Representative Engagements|url=http://www.bakerbotts.com/william-h-jeffress/|publisher=Baker Botts L.L.P.|accessdate=7 June 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120805115906/http://www.bakerbotts.com/william-h-jeffress/|archivedate=5 August 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2010, Salman underwent [[spinal surgery]] in the [[United States]] and remained out of the kingdom for recovery.<ref name=ginm>{{cite news|title=King Sulayman bin Abdulaziz undergone successful surgery, Royal Court statement says|url=http://www.gulfinthemedia.com/index.php?m=gcc_press&id=2271052&cnt=171&lang=en&PHPSESSID=6ae1931c79dcdc291ac1f3b9d2d1e5fb|accessdate=26 May 2012|work=Gulf in the Media|date=17 August 2010}}</ref> He has had one [[stroke]] and despite receiving physiotherapy; his left arm does not work as well as his right.<ref>{{cite web|last=Henderson|first=Simon|title=The Man Who Would Be King|url=https://foreignpolicy.com/articles/2012/04/10/the_man_who_would_be_king|work=Foreign Policy|accessdate=12 April 2012|date=10 April 2012}}</ref><ref name=hen10jan>{{cite news|last=Henderson|first=Simon|title=To Stop Iran, Get a New Saudi King|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/international/archive/2013/01/to-stop-iran-get-a-new-saudi-king/267013/|accessdate=19 April 2013|newspaper=The Atlantic|date=10 January 2013}}</ref><ref>[https://www.economist.com/news/middle-east-and-africa/21600180-king-abdullah-appoints-second-line-throne-next-after-next Next after next\u2026] ''The Economist'' (Cairo). 5 April 2014. Retrieved 4 August 2014.</ref> Salman also suffers from mild [[dementia]],<ref>{{cite news|author=David Ignatius|title=A 30-year-old Saudi prince could jump-start the kingdom \u2014 or drive it off a cliff|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/global-opinions/a-30-year-old-saudi-prince-could-jump-start-the-kingdom--or-drive-it-off-a-cliff/2016/06/28/ce669a3e-3c69-11e6-a66f-aa6c1883b6b1_story.html|accessdate=20 May 2016|work=The Washington Post|date=28 June 2016}}</ref> specifically [[Alzheimer's disease|Alzheimer's]].<ref name=\"A family revolt could bring down the Saudi monarchy\">{{cite news|last1=Miles|first1=Hugh|title=A family revolt could bring down the Saudi monarchy|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/middle-east/saudi-arabia-power-struggle-between-king-salman-and-mohammed-bin-salman-could-bring-down-the-a6706801.html|accessdate=21 September 2016|date=23 October 2015}}</ref>\n\nUS intelligence officials believe that King Salman has been kept apart from his wife Princess Fahda bint Falah Al Hathleen for several years, on the orders of their son Prince Mohammad bin Salman.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/world/u-s-officials-saudi-crown-prince-has-hidden-his-mother-n847391 |title=U.S. officials: Saudi crown prince has hidden his mother from his father, the king |publisher=Nbcnews.com |date= |accessdate=2018-06-27}}</ref> He was reportedly concerned that she opposed his plans for a power grab that could divide the royal family, and might have tried to prevent it. The officials interviewed said the prince placed his mother under [[house arrest]] without the king's knowledge.\n\nSalman received the Lifetime Achievement Award of the Al-Turath Charity Foundation in the field of urban heritage in 2013.<ref name=nbhf>{{cite web|title=Crown Prince receives Lifetime Achievement Award in the field of Urban Heritage|url=http://www.nbhf.org.sa/english/LatestNews.aspx?id=965|work=National Built Heritage Forum|access-date=17 July 2013}}</ref> In 2017, Salman pledged US$15,000,000 for [[Rohingya people|Rohingya Muslim]] refugees in [[Bangladesh]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://world.einnews.com/article__detail/country/saudiarabia/404985252-saudi-arabia-pledges-15-million-to-aid-rohingya-muslims-in-myanmar?vcode=PqS0|title=Saudi Arabia Pledges $15 Million to Aid Rohingya Muslims in Myanmar|first=EIN|last=News|date=20 September 2017|website=einnews.com}}</ref>\n\n==Titles, Styles and Honours==\n\n===Titles and Styles===\n*31 December 1935 - 18 June 2012: ''His Royal Highness'' Prince Salman bin Abdulaziz\n*18 June 2012 - 23 January 2015: ''His Royal Highness'' The Crown Prince of Saudi Arabia\n*23 January 2015 \u2013 present: ''Custodian of the Two Holy Mosques'' The King of Saudi Arabia\n** In diplomatic parlance: ''His Majesty'' The King of Saudi Arabia\n\n===Foreign honour===\n* {{flagu|Bahrain}} : \n** Collar of the Order of Isa bin Salman Al Khalifa (2016)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gdnonline.com/Details/148451/In-Pictures-Saudi-King-Salman-begins-official-visit-to-Bahrain/168470|title=Saudi King Salman begins official visit to Bahrain}}</ref>\n* {{flagu|Bangladesh}} : \n** Collar of the Order of the Republic (2018)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://english.alarabiya.net/en/News/gulf/2018/10/17/King-Salman-receives-Bangladesh-PM-holds-luncheon-honoring-her.html|title=Saudi King Salman receives Bangladesh PM, holds lunch in her honor}}</ref>\n* {{flagu|Brunei}} : \n** [[List of post-nominal letters (Brunei)|Royal Family Order of the Crown of Brunei]] (D.K.M.B.) (2017) <ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.pelitabrunei.gov.bn/Lists/Berita/NewDisplayForm.aspx?ID=807 |title=Berkenan menerima kunjungan muhibah Kebawah DYMM Raja Salman bin Abdulaziz Al-Saud |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=4 March 2017 |website=[[Pelita Brunei]] |language=Malay |access-date=23 February 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190204015226/http://www.pelitabrunei.gov.bn/Lists/Berita/NewDisplayForm.aspx?ID=807 |archive-date=4 February 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n* {{flagu|Djibouti}} : \n** Grand Cordon of the Order of National Star of Djibouti (2015)<ref>{{cite web|url=King Salman holds talks with Djibouti leader|title=King Salman holds talks with Djibouti leader}}</ref>\n* {{flagu|Egypt}} : \n** Collar of the [[Order of the Nile]] (2016)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://english.ahram.org.eg/NewsAFCON/2017/199078.aspx|title=Egypt's Sisi awards Saudi King Salman 'Order of the Nile' honour}}</ref>\n* {{flagu|Guinea}} : \n** Grand Cordon of the National Order of Merit (2015)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.arabnews.com/featured/news/898451|title=Top Guinea medal for King}}</ref>\n* {{flagu|Indonesia}} : \n** [[Star of the Republic of Indonesia]], 1st class (2017)<ref>{{cite web\n|url=http://english.astroawani.com/world-news/saudi-king-salman-increases-indonesias-haj-quota-134249|title=Saudi King Salman increases Indonesia's haj quota}}</ref>\n* {{flagu|Japan}} : \n** Grand Cordon of the [[Order of the Chrysanthemum]] (2017)<ref>{{cite web\n|url=http://www.arabnews.com/node/1067571/saudi-arabia|title=King Salman to hold talks with Japanese premier today}}</ref>\n* {{flagu|Jordan}} : \n** Collar of the [[Order of Al-Hussein bin Ali]] (2017)<ref>{{cite web\n|url=https://english.alarabiya.net/en/News/gulf/2017/03/28/King-Salman-holds-the-highest-award-in-Jordan.html\n|title=Saudi Arabia's King Salman receives Jordan's highest award}}</ref>\n* {{flagu|Kuwait}} : \n** Collar of the [[Order of Kuwait]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://saudigazette.com.sa/article/168929|title=Kuwaiti Crown Prince hosts banquet in honor of King Salman}}</ref>\n* {{flagu|Malaysia}} : \n** Honorary Commander of the [[Order of the Defender of the Realm#Commander|Order of the Defender of the Realm]] (P.M.N.) (1982)<ref name=\"istiadat.gov.my\">{{cite web\n|url=http://www.istiadat.gov.my/index.php/component/semakanlantikanskp/|title=Semakan Penerima Darjah Kebesaran, Bintang dan Pingat}}</ref>\n** [[Order of the Crown of the Realm|The Most Exalted Order of the Crown of the Realm]] (D.M.N.) (2017)<ref name=\"istiadat.gov.my\"/>\n* {{flagu|Mexico}} : \n** Collar of the [[Order of the Aztec Eagle]] (2016)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.arabnews.com/featured/news/866441|title=Mexico eyes Gulf investment funds}}</ref>\n* {{flagu|Morocco}} : \n** Grand Cordon of the [[Order of Ouissam Alaouite]] (1987)<ref name=\"bilateralchamber.org\">{{cite web\n|url=http://bilateralchamber.org/new-king-saudi-arabia-h-e-king-salman-bin-abdulaziz-al-saud/|title=A New King for Saudi Arabia: H.E. King Salman bin Abdulaziz Al Saud}}</ref>\n** Collar of the [[Order of Muhammad]] (2016)<ref>{{cite 